/web/html/global_attributes/accesskey.summary: The `accesskey` global attribute provides a hint for generating a keyboard shortcut for the current element. The attribute value must consist of a single printable character (which includes accented and other characters that can be generated by the keyboard).
/web/html/global_attributes/accesskey.name: accesskey

/web/html/global_attributes/autocapitali.summary: The `autocapitalize` global attribute is an enumerated attribute that controls whether and how text input is automatically capitalized as it is entered/edited by the user.
/web/html/global_attributes/autocapitali.name: autocapitalize

/web/html/global_attributes/autofocus.summary: The `autofocus` global attribute is a Boolean attribute indicating that an element should be focused on page load, or when the dialog that it is part of is displayed.
/web/html/global_attributes/autofocus.name: autofocus

/web/html/global_attributes/class.summary: The `class` global attribute is a space-separated list of the case-sensitive classes of the element. Classes allow CSS and Javascript to select and access specific elements via the class selectors or functions like the DOM method document.getElementsByClassName.
/web/html/global_attributes/class.name: class

/web/html/global_attributes/contentedita.summary: The `contenteditable` global attribute is an enumerated attribute indicating if the element should be editable by the user. If so, the browser modifies its widget to allow editing.
/web/html/global_attributes/contentedita.name: contenteditable

/web/html/global_attributes/contextmenu.summary: Warning: The contextmenu attribute is obsolete and will be removed from all browsers
/web/html/global_attributes/contextmenu.name: contextmenu

/web/html/global_attributes/data-*.summary: The `data-*` global attributes form a class of attributes called custom data attributes, that allow proprietary information to be exchanged between the HTML and its DOM representation by scripts.
/web/html/global_attributes/data-*.name: data-*

/web/html/global_attributes/dir.summary: The `dir` global attribute is an enumerated attribute that indicates the directionality of the element's text.
/web/html/global_attributes/dir.name: dir

/web/html/global_attributes/draggable.summary: The draggable global attribute is an enumerated attribute that indicates whether the element can be dragged, either with native browser behavior or the HTML Drag and Drop API.
/web/html/global_attributes/draggable.name: draggable

/web/html/global_attributes/enterkeyhint.summary: The `enterkeyhint` global attribute is an enumerated attribute defining what action label (or icon) to present for the enter key on virtual keyboards.
/web/html/global_attributes/enterkeyhint.name: enterkeyhint

/web/html/global_attributes/exportparts.summary: Used to transitively export shadow parts from a nested shadow tree into a containing light tree.
/web/html/global_attributes/exportparts.name: exportparts

/web/html/global_attributes/hidden.summary: The `hidden` global attribute is a Boolean attribute indicating that the element is not yet, or is no longer, relevant. For example, it can be used to hide elements of the page that can't be used until the login process has been completed. Browsers won't render elements with the `hidden` attribute set.
/web/html/global_attributes/hidden.name: hidden

/web/html/global_attributes/id.summary: The `id` global attribute defines an identifier (ID) which must be unique in the whole document. Its purpose is to identify the element when linking (using a fragment identifier), scripting, or styling (with CSS).
/web/html/global_attributes/id.name: id

/web/html/global_attributes/inputmode.summary: The `inputmode` global attribute is an enumerated attribute that hints at the type of data that might be entered by the user while editing the element or its contents. This allows a browser to display an appropriate virtual keyboard.
/web/html/global_attributes/inputmode.name: inputmode

/web/html/global_attributes/is.summary: The `is` global attribute allows you to specify that a standard HTML element should behave like a defined custom built-in element (see Using custom elements for more details).
/web/html/global_attributes/is.name: is

/web/html/global_attributes/itemid.summary: The `itemid` global attribute provides microdata in the form of a unique, global identifier of an item.
/web/html/global_attributes/itemid.name: itemid

/web/html/global_attributes/itemprop.summary: The `itemprop` global attribute is used to add properties to an item. Every HTML element can have an `itemprop` attribute specified, and an `itemprop` consists of a name-value pair. Each name-value pair is called a property, and a group of one or more properties forms an item. Property values are either a string or a URL and can be associated with a very wide range of elements including audio, embed, iframe, img, link, object, source , track, and video.
/web/html/global_attributes/itemprop.name: itemprop

/web/html/global_attributes/itemref.summary: Properties that are not descendants of an element with the itemscope attribute can be associated with an item using the global attribute `itemref`.
/web/html/global_attributes/itemref.name: itemref

/web/html/global_attributes/itemscope.summary: `itemscope` is a boolean global attribute that defines the scope of associated metadata. Specifying the `itemscope` attribute for an element creates a new item, which results in a number of name-value pairs that are associated with the element.
/web/html/global_attributes/itemscope.name: itemscope

/web/html/global_attributes/itemtype.summary: The global attribute `itemtype` specifies the URL of the vocabulary that will be used to define `itemprop`'s (item properties) in the data structure.
/web/html/global_attributes/itemtype.name: itemtype

/web/html/global_attributes/lang.summary: The `lang` global attribute helps define the language of an element: the language that non-editable elements are written in, or the language that the editable elements should be written in by the user. The attribute contains a single "language tag" in the format defined in RFC 5646 "Tags for Identifying Languages (also known as BCP 47)".
/web/html/global_attributes/lang.name: lang

/web/html/global_attributes/nonce.summary: The `nonce` global attribute is a content attribute defining a cryptographic nonce ("number used once") which can be used by Content Security Policy to determine whether or not a given fetch will be allowed to proceed for a given element.
/web/html/global_attributes/nonce.name: nonce

/web/html/global_attributes/part.summary: The `part` global attribute contains a space-separated list of the part names of the element. Part names allows CSS to select and style specific elements in a shadow tree via the ::part pseudo-element.
/web/html/global_attributes/part.name: part

/web/html/global_attributes/slot.summary: The `slot` global attribute assigns a slot in a shadow DOM shadow tree to an element: An element with a `slot` attribute is assigned to the slot created by the slot element whose name attribute's value matches that `slot` attribute's value.
/web/html/global_attributes/slot.name: slot

/web/html/global_attributes/spellcheck.summary: The `spellcheck` global attribute is an enumerated attribute defines whether the element may be checked for spelling errors.
/web/html/global_attributes/spellcheck.name: spellcheck

/web/html/global_attributes/style.summary: The `style` global attribute contains CSS styling declarations to be applied to the element. Note that it is recommended for styles to be defined in a separate file or files. This attribute and the style element have mainly the purpose of allowing for quick styling, for example for testing purposes.
/web/html/global_attributes/style.name: style

/web/html/global_attributes/tabindex.summary: The `tabindex` global attribute indicates that its element can be focused, and where it participates in sequential keyboard navigation (usually with the <kbd>Tab</kbd> key, hence the name).
/web/html/global_attributes/tabindex.name: tabindex

/web/html/global_attributes/title.summary: The `title` global attribute contains text representing advisory information related to the element it belongs to.
/web/html/global_attributes/title.name: title

/web/html/global_attributes/translate.summary: The `translate` global attribute is an enumerated attribute that is used to specify whether an element's translatable attribute values and its Text node children should be translated when the page is localized, or whether to leave them unchanged.
/web/html/global_attributes/translate.name: translate

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onabort.summary: The `onabort` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing abort events sent to the window.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onabort.name: onabort

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onblur.summary: The `onblur` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing blur events. It's available on Element, Document, and Window.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onblur.name: onblur

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oncancel.summary: The `oncancel` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler for processing cancel events sent to a dialog element.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oncancel.name: oncancel

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oncanplay.summary: The `oncanplay` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing canplay events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oncanplay.name: oncanplay

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oncanplayth.summary: The `oncanplaythrough` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing canplaythrough events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oncanplayth.name: oncanplaythrough

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onchange.summary: The `onchange` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler for processing change events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onchange.name: onchange

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onclick.summary: The `onclick` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing Element/click_event events on a given element.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onclick.name: onclick

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onclose.summary: The `onclose` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler for processing close events sent to a dialog element.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onclose.name: onclose

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oncontextme.summary: The `oncontextmenu` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes contextmenu events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oncontextme.name: oncontextmenu

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondblclick.summary: The `ondblclick` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes dblclick events on the given element.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondblclick.name: ondblclick

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondrag.summary: A global event handler for the drag event.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondrag.name: ondrag

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragend.summary: A global event handler for the dragend event.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragend.name: ondragend

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragenter.summary: A global event handler for the dragenter event.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragenter.name: ondragenter

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragleave.summary: A global event handler for the dragleave event.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragleave.name: ondragleave

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragover.summary: A global event handler for the dragover event.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragover.name: ondragover

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragstart.summary: A global event handler for the dragstart event.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondragstart.name: ondragstart

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondrop.summary: A global event handler for the drop event.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondrop.name: ondrop

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondurationc.summary: The `ondurationchange` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing durationchange events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/ondurationc.name: ondurationchange

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onemptied.summary: The `onemptied` property sets and returns the event handler for the `emptied` event.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onemptied.name: onemptied

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onended.summary: The `onended` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing ended events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onended.name: onended

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onerror.summary: The `onerror` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes error events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onerror.name: onerror

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onfocus.summary: The `onfocus` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes focus events on the given element.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onfocus.name: onfocus

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oninput.summary: The `oninput` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes input events on the input, select, and textarea elements. It also handles these events on elements where {{domxref("HTMLElement.contentEditable",
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oninput.name: oninput

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oninvalid.summary: The `oninvalid` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes invalid events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/oninvalid.name: oninvalid

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onkeydown.summary: The `onkeydown` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes keydown events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onkeydown.name: onkeydown

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onkeypress.summary: The `onkeypress` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes keypress events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onkeypress.name: onkeypress

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onkeyup.summary: The `onkeyup` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes keyup events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onkeyup.name: onkeyup

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onload.summary: The `onload` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes Window/load_event events on a Window, XMLHttpRequest, img element, etc.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onload.name: onload

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onloadeddat.summary: The `onloadeddata` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing loadeddata events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onloadeddat.name: onloadeddata

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onloadedmet.summary: The `onloadedmetadata` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing loadedmetadata events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onloadedmet.name: onloadedmetadata

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onloadstart.summary: The `onloadstart` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler representing the code to be called when the loadstart event is raised (when progress has begun on the loading of a resource.)
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onloadstart.name: onloadstart

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmousedown.summary: The `onmousedown` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes mousedown events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmousedown.name: onmousedown

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseente.summary: The `onmouseenter` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing mouseenter events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseente.name: onmouseenter

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseleav.summary: The `onmouseleave` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing mouseleave events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseleav.name: onmouseleave

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmousemove.summary: The `onmousemove` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes mousemove events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmousemove.name: onmousemove

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseout.summary: The `onmouseout` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes mouseout events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseout.name: onmouseout

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseover.summary: The `onmouseover` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes mouseover events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseover.name: onmouseover

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseup.summary: The `onmouseup` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes mouseup events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmouseup.name: onmouseup

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmousewhee.summary: The onmousewheel property sets and returns the event handler for the mousewheel event.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onmousewhee.name: onmousewheel

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onpause.summary: The `onpause` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing pause events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onpause.name: onpause

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onplay.summary: The `onplay` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing play events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onplay.name: onplay

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onplaying.summary: The `onplaying` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is the event handler for processing playing events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onplaying.name: onplaying

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onreset.summary: The `onreset` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes reset events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onreset.name: onreset

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onresize.summary: The `onresize` property of the GlobalEventHandlers interface is an event handler that processes `resize` events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onresize.name: onresize

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onscroll.summary: The `onscroll` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes `scroll` events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onscroll.name: onscroll

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onselect.summary: The `onselect` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes `select` events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onselect.name: onselect

/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onsubmit.summary: The `onsubmit` property of the GlobalEventHandlers mixin is an event handler that processes submit events.
/web/api/globaleventhandlers/onsubmit.name: onsubmit

/web/accessibility/aria/roles.summary: ARIA roles provide semantic meaning to content, allowing screen readers and other tools to present and support interaction with object in a way that is consistent with user expectations of that type of object. ARIA roles can be used to describe elements that don't natively exist in HTML or exist but don't yet have full browser support.
/web/accessibility/aria/roles.name: role

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: In ARIA live regions, the global `aria-atomic` attribute indicates whether assistive technologies such as a screen reader will present all, or only parts of, the changed region based on the change notifications defined by the `aria-relevant` attribute.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-atomic

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: Used in ARIA live regions, the global `aria-busy` state indicates an element is being modified and that assistive technologies may want to wait until the changes are complete before informing the user about the update.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-busy

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The global `aria-controls` property identifies the element (or elements) whose contents or presence are controlled by the element on which this attribute is set.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-controls

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: A non-null `aria-current` state on an element indicates that this element represents the current item within a container or set of related elements.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-current

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The global `aria-describedby` attribute identifies the element (or elements) that describes the element on which the attribute is set.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-describedby

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The global `aria-description` attribute defines a string value that describes or annotates the current element.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-description

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The global `aria-details` attribute identifies the element (or elements) that provide additional information related to the object.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-details

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-disabled` state indicates that the element is perceivable but disabled, so it is not editable or otherwise operable.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-disabled

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The global `aria-dropeffect` attribute indicates what functions may be performed when a dragged object is released on the drop target.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-dropeffect

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-errormessage` attribute on an object identifies the element that provides an error message for that object.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-errormessage

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The global `aria-flowto` attribute identifies the next element (or elements) in an alternate reading order of content. This allows assistive technology to override the general default of reading in document source order at the user's discretion.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-flowto

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-grabbed` state indicates an element's "grabbed" state in a drag-and-drop operation.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-grabbed

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-haspopup` attribute indicates the availability and type of interactive popup element that can be triggered by the element on which the attribute is set.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-haspopup

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-hidden` state indicates whether the element is exposed to an accessibility API.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-hidden

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-invalid` state indicates the entered value does not conform to the format expected by the application.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-invalid

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The global `aria-keyshortcuts` attribute indicates keyboard shortcuts that an author has implemented to activate or give focus to an element.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-keyshortcuts

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-label` attribute defines a string value that labels an interactive element.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-label

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-labelledby` attribute identifies the element (or elements) that labels the element it is applied to.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-labelledby

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The global `aria-live` attribute indicates that an element will be updated, and describes the types of updates the user agents, assistive technologies, and user can expect from the live region.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-live

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-owns` attribute identifies an element (or elements) in order to define a visual, functional, or contextual relationship between a parent and its child elements when the DOM hierarchy cannot be used to represent the relationship.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-owns

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: Used in ARIA live regions, the global `aria-relevant` attribute indicates what notifications the user agent will trigger when the accessibility tree within a live region is modified.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-relevant

/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.summary: The `aria-roledescription` attribute defines a human-readable, author-localized description for the role of an element.
/web/accessibility/aria/attributes/aria-.name: aria-roledescription

/web/svg/attribute/class.summary: Assigns a class name or set of class names to an element. You may assign the same class name or names to any number of elements, however, multiple class names must be separated by whitespace characters.
/web/svg/attribute/class.name: class

/web/svg/attribute/style.summary: The `style` attribute allows to style an element using CSS declarations. It functions identically to the `style` attribute in HTML.
/web/svg/attribute/style.name: style

/web/svg/attribute/id.summary: The `id` attribute assigns a unique name to an element.
/web/svg/attribute/id.name: id

/web/svg/attribute/lang.summary: The `lang` attribute specifies the primary language used in contents and attributes containing text content of particular elements.
/web/svg/attribute/lang.name: lang

/web/svg/attribute/tabindex.summary: The `tabindex` attribute allows you to control whether an element is focusable and to define the relative order of the element for the purposes of sequential focus navigation.
/web/svg/attribute/tabindex.name: tabindex

/web/svg/attribute/xml:base.summary: The `xml:base` attribute specifies a base IRI other than the base IRI of the document or external entity.
/web/svg/attribute/xml:base.name: xml:base

/web/svg/attribute/xml:lang.summary: The `xml:lang` attribute specifies the primary language used in contents and attributes containing text content of particular elements.
/web/svg/attribute/xml:lang.name: xml:lang

/web/svg/attribute/xml:space.summary: SVG supports the built-in XML `xml:space` attribute to handle whitespace characters inside elements. Child elements inside an element may also have an `xml:space` attribute that overrides the parent's one.
/web/svg/attribute/xml:space.name: xml:space

/web/html/element/a.name: a
/web/html/element/a.summary: The `<a>` HTML element (or anchor element), with its `href` attribute, creates a hyperlink to web pages, files, email addresses, locations in the same page, or anything else a URL can address.

/web/html/element/a/attributes/download.name: download
/web/html/element/a/attributes/download.summary: Causes the browser to treat the linked URL as a download. Can be used with or without a value.

/web/html/element/a/attributes/href.name: href
/web/html/element/a/attributes/href.summary: The URL that the hyperlink points to. Links are not restricted to HTTP-based URLs  they can use any URL scheme supported by browsers.

/web/html/element/a/attributes/hreflang.name: hreflang
/web/html/element/a/attributes/hreflang.summary: Hints at the human language of the linked URL. No built-in functionality. Allowed values are the same as the global `lang` attribute.

/web/html/element/a/attributes/ping.name: ping
/web/html/element/a/attributes/ping.summary: A space-separated list of URLs. When the link is followed, the browser will send POST requests with the body `PING` to the URLs. Typically for tracking.

/web/html/element/a/attributes/referrerp.name: referrerpolicy
/web/html/element/a/attributes/referrerp.summary: How much of the referrer to send when following the link.

/web/html/element/a/attributes/rel.name: rel
/web/html/element/a/attributes/rel.summary: The relationship of the linked URL as space-separated link types.

/web/html/element/a/attributes/target.name: target
/web/html/element/a/attributes/target.summary: Where to display the linked URL, as the name for a browsing context (a tab, window, or iframe). The following keywords have special meanings for where to load the URL.

/web/html/element/a/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/a/attributes/type.summary: Hints at the linked URL's format with a MIME type. No built-in functionality.

/web/html/element/abbr.name: abbr
/web/html/element/abbr.summary: The `<abbr>` HTML element represents an abbreviation or acronym; the optional title attribute can provide an expansion or description for the abbreviation. If present, `title` must contain this full description and nothing else.

/web/html/element/acronym.name: acronym
/web/html/element/acronym.summary: The `<acronym>` HTML element allows authors to clearly indicate a sequence of characters that compose an acronym or abbreviation for a word.

/web/html/element/address.name: address
/web/html/element/address.summary: The `<address>` HTML element indicates that the enclosed HTML provides contact information for a person or people, or for an organization.

/web/html/element/applet.name: applet
/web/html/element/applet.summary: The obsolete HTML Applet Element (`<applet>`) embeds a Java applet into the document; this element has been deprecated in favor of object.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/alig.name: align
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/alig.summary: This attribute is used to position the applet on the page relative to content that might flow around it. The HTML 4.01 specification defines values of `bottom`, `left`, `middle`, `right`, and `top`, whereas Microsoft and Netscape also might support `absbottom`, `absmiddle`, `baseline`, `center`, and `texttop`.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/alt.name: alt
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/alt.summary: This attribute causes a descriptive text alternate to be displayed on browsers that do not support Java. Page designers should also remember that content enclosed within the `<applet>` element may also be rendered as alternative text.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/arch.name: archive
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/arch.summary: This attribute refers to an archived or compressed version of the applet and its associated class files, which might help reduce download time.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/code.name: code
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/code.summary: This attribute specifies the URL of the applet's class file to be loaded and executed. Applet filenames are identified by a .class filename extension. The URL specified by code might be relative to the `codebase` attribute.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/code.name: codebase
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/code.summary: This attribute gives the absolute or relative URL of the directory where applets' .class files referenced by the code attribute are stored.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/data.name: datafld
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/data.summary: This attribute, supported by Internet Explorer 4 and higher, specifies the column name from the data source object that supplies the bound data. This attribute might be used to specify the various param elements passed to the Java applet.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/data.name: datasrc
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/data.summary: Like `datafld`, this attribute is used for data binding under Internet Explorer 4. It indicates the id of the data source object that supplies the data that is bound to the param elements associated with the applet.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/heig.name: height
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/heig.summary: This attribute specifies the height, in pixels, that the applet needs.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/hspa.name: hspace
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/hspa.summary: This attribute specifies additional horizontal space, in pixels, to be reserved on either side of the applet.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/mays.name: mayscript
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/mays.summary: In the Netscape implementation, this attribute allows access to an applet by programs in a scripting language embedded in the document.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/name.summary: This attribute assigns a name to the applet so that it can be identified by other resources; particularly scripts.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/obje.name: object
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/obje.summary: This attribute specifies the URL of a serialized representation of an applet.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/src.summary: As defined for Internet Explorer 4 and higher, this attribute specifies a URL for an associated file for the applet. The meaning and use is unclear and not part of the HTML standard.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/vspa.name: vspace
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/vspa.summary: This attribute specifies additional vertical space, in pixels, to be reserved above and below the applet.

/web/html/element/applet/attributes/widt.name: width
/web/html/element/applet/attributes/widt.summary: This attribute specifies in pixels the width that the applet needs.

/web/html/element/area.name: area
/web/html/element/area.summary: The `<area>` HTML element defines an area inside an image map that has predefined clickable areas. An image map allows geometric areas on an image to be associated with Hyperlink.

/web/html/element/area/attributes/alt.name: alt
/web/html/element/area/attributes/alt.summary: A text string alternative to display on browsers that do not display images.

/web/html/element/area/attributes/coords.name: coords
/web/html/element/area/attributes/coords.summary: The `coords` attribute details the coordinates of the `shape` attribute in size, shape, and placement of an `<area>`.

/web/html/element/area/attributes/downlo.name: download
/web/html/element/area/attributes/downlo.summary: This attribute, if present, indicates that the author intends the hyperlink to be used for downloading a resource.

/web/html/element/area/attributes/href.name: href
/web/html/element/area/attributes/href.summary: The hyperlink target for the area.

/web/html/element/area/attributes/hrefla.name: hreflang
/web/html/element/area/attributes/hrefla.summary: Indicates the language of the linked resource. Allowed values are defined by RFC 5646 "Tags for Identifying Languages (also known as BCP 47)".

/web/html/element/area/attributes/ping.name: ping
/web/html/element/area/attributes/ping.summary: Contains a space-separated list of URLs to which, when the hyperlink is followed, POST requests with the body `PING` will be sent by the browser (in the background).

/web/html/element/area/attributes/referr.name: referrerpolicy
/web/html/element/area/attributes/referr.summary: A string indicating which referrer to use when fetching the resource.

/web/html/element/area/attributes/rel.name: rel
/web/html/element/area/attributes/rel.summary: For anchors containing the href attribute, this attribute specifies the relationship of the target object to the link object.

/web/html/element/area/attributes/shape.name: shape
/web/html/element/area/attributes/shape.summary: The shape of the associated hot spot. The specifications for HTML defines the values `rect`, which defines a rectangular region; `circle`, which defines a circular region; `poly`, which defines a polygon; and `default`, which indicates the entire region beyond any defined shapes.

/web/html/element/area/attributes/target.name: target
/web/html/element/area/attributes/target.summary: A keyword or author-defined name of the browsing context to display the linked resource.

/web/html/element/article.name: article
/web/html/element/article.summary: The `<article>` HTML element represents a self-contained composition in a document, page, application, or site, which is intended to be independently distributable or reusable (e.g., in syndication). Examples include: a forum post, a magazine or newspaper article, or a blog entry, a product card, a user-submitted comment, an interactive widget or gadget, or any other independent item of content.

/web/html/element/aside.name: aside
/web/html/element/aside.summary: The `<aside>` HTML element represents a portion of a document whose content is only indirectly related to the document's main content. Asides are frequently presented as sidebars or call-out boxes.

/web/html/element/audio.name: audio
/web/html/element/audio.summary: The `<audio>` HTML element is used to embed sound content in documents. It may contain one or more audio sources, represented using the `src` attribute or the source element: the browser will choose the most suitable one. It can also be the destination for streamed media, using a MediaStream.

/web/html/element/audio/attributes/autop.name: autoplay
/web/html/element/audio/attributes/autop.summary: A Boolean attribute: if specified, the audio will automatically begin playback as soon as it can do so, without waiting for the entire audio file to finish downloading.

/web/html/element/audio/attributes/contr.name: controls
/web/html/element/audio/attributes/contr.summary: If this attribute is present, the browser will offer controls to allow the user to control audio playback, including volume, seeking, and pause/resume playback.

/web/html/element/audio/attributes/cross.name: crossorigin
/web/html/element/audio/attributes/cross.summary: This enumerated attribute indicates whether to use CORS to fetch the related audio file. CORS-enabled resources can be reused in the canvas element without being tainted. The allowed values are.

/web/html/element/audio/attributes/disab.name: disableremoteplayback
/web/html/element/audio/attributes/disab.summary: A Boolean attribute used to disable the capability of remote playback in devices that are attached using wired (HDMI, DVI, etc.) and wireless technologies (Miracast, Chromecast, DLNA, AirPlay, etc). See this proposed specification for more information.

/web/html/element/audio/attributes/loop.name: loop
/web/html/element/audio/attributes/loop.summary: A Boolean attribute: if specified, the audio player will automatically seek back to the start upon reaching the end of the audio.

/web/html/element/audio/attributes/muted.name: muted
/web/html/element/audio/attributes/muted.summary: A Boolean attribute that indicates whether the audio will be initially silenced. Its default value is `false`.

/web/html/element/audio/attributes/prelo.name: preload
/web/html/element/audio/attributes/prelo.summary: This enumerated attribute is intended to provide a hint to the browser about what the author thinks will lead to the best user experience. It may have one of the following values.

/web/html/element/audio/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/audio/attributes/src.summary: The URL of the audio to embed. This is subject to HTTP access controls. This is optional; you may instead use the source element within the audio block to specify the audio to embed.

/web/html/element/b.name: b
/web/html/element/b.summary: The `<b>` HTML element is used to draw the reader's attention to the element's contents, which are not otherwise granted special importance. This was formerly known as the Boldface element, and most browsers still draw the text in boldface. However, you should not use `<b>` for styling text; instead, you should use the CSS font-weight property to create boldface text, or the strong element to indicate that text is of special importance.

/web/html/element/base.name: base
/web/html/element/base.summary: The `<base>` HTML element specifies the base URL to use for all relative URLs in a document. There can be only one `<base>` element in a document.

/web/html/element/base/attributes/href.name: href
/web/html/element/base/attributes/href.summary: The base URL to be used throughout the document for relative URLs. Absolute and relative URLs are allowed.

/web/html/element/base/attributes/target.name: target
/web/html/element/base/attributes/target.summary: A keyword or author-defined name of the default browsing context to show the results of navigation from a, area, or form elements without explicit `target` attributes. The following keywords have special meanings.

/web/html/element/basefont.name: basefont
/web/html/element/basefont.summary: The `<basefont>` HTML element is deprecated. It sets a default font face, size, and color for the other elements which are descended from its parent element. With this set, the font's size can then be varied relative to the base size using the font element.

/web/html/element/basefont/attributes/co.name: color
/web/html/element/basefont/attributes/co.summary: This attribute sets the text color using either a named color or a color specified in the hexadecimal #RRGGBB format.

/web/html/element/basefont/attributes/fa.name: face
/web/html/element/basefont/attributes/fa.summary: This attribute contains a list of one or more font names. The document text in the default style is rendered in the first font face that the client's browser supports. If no font listed is installed on the local system, the browser typically defaults to the proportional or fixed-width font for that system.

/web/html/element/basefont/attributes/si.name: size
/web/html/element/basefont/attributes/si.summary: This attribute specifies the font size as either a numeric or relative value. Numeric values range from 1 to 7 with 1 being the smallest and 3 the default.

/web/html/element/bdi.name: bdi
/web/html/element/bdi.summary: The `<bdi>` HTML element tells the browser's bidirectional algorithm to treat the text it contains in isolation from its surrounding text. It's particularly useful when a website dynamically inserts some text and doesn't know the directionality of the text being inserted.

/web/html/element/bdo.name: bdo
/web/html/element/bdo.summary: The `<bdo>` HTML element overrides the current directionality of text, so that the text within is rendered in a different direction.

/web/html/element/bdo/attributes/dir.name: dir
/web/html/element/bdo/attributes/dir.summary: The direction in which text should be rendered in this element's contents. Possible values are.

/web/html/element/bgsound.name: bgsound
/web/html/element/bgsound.summary: The `<bgsound>` HTML element is deprecated. It sets up a sound file to play in the background while the page is used; use audio instead.

/web/html/element/bgsound/attributes/bal.name: balance
/web/html/element/bgsound/attributes/bal.summary: This attribute defines a number between -10,000 and +10,000 that determines how the volume will be divided between the speakers.

/web/html/element/bgsound/attributes/loo.name: loop
/web/html/element/bgsound/attributes/loo.summary: This attribute indicates the number of times a sound is to be played and either has a numeric value or the keyword infinite.

/web/html/element/bgsound/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/bgsound/attributes/src.summary: This attribute specifies the URL of the sound file to be played, which must be one of the following types: .wav, .au, or .mid.

/web/html/element/bgsound/attributes/vol.name: volume
/web/html/element/bgsound/attributes/vol.summary: This attribute defines a number between -10,000 and 0 that determines the loudness of a page's background sound.

/web/html/element/big.name: big
/web/html/element/big.summary: The `<big>` HTML deprecated element renders the enclosed text at a font size one level larger than the surrounding text (`medium` becomes `large`, for example). The size is capped at the browser's maximum permitted font size.

/web/html/element/blink.name: blink
/web/html/element/blink.summary: The `<blink>` HTML element is a non-standard element which causes the enclosed text to flash slowly.

/web/html/element/blockquote.name: blockquote
/web/html/element/blockquote.summary: The `<blockquote>` HTML element indicates that the enclosed text is an extended quotation. Usually, this is rendered visually by indentation (see Notes for how to change it). A URL for the source of the quotation may be given using the cite attribute, while a text representation of the source can be given using the cite element.

/web/html/element/blockquote/attributes/.name: cite
/web/html/element/blockquote/attributes/.summary: A URL that designates a source document or message for the information quoted. This attribute is intended to point to information explaining the context or the reference for the quote.

/web/html/element/body.name: body
/web/html/element/body.summary: The `<body>` HTML element represents the content of an HTML document. There can be only one `<body>` element in a document.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/alink.name: alink
/web/html/element/body/attributes/alink.summary: Color of text for hyperlinks when selected.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/backgr.name: background
/web/html/element/body/attributes/backgr.summary: URI of a image to use as a background.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/bottom.name: bottommargin
/web/html/element/body/attributes/bottom.summary: The margin of the bottom of the body.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/leftma.name: leftmargin
/web/html/element/body/attributes/leftma.summary: The margin of the left of the body.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/link.name: link
/web/html/element/body/attributes/link.summary: Color of text for unvisited hypertext links.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onafte.name: onafterprint
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onafte.summary: Function to call after the user has printed the document.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onbefo.name: onbeforeprint
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onbefo.summary: Function to call when the user requests printing of the document.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onbefo.name: onbeforeunload
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onbefo.summary: Function to call when the document is about to be unloaded.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onblur.name: onblur
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onblur.summary: Function to call when the document loses focus.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onerro.name: onerror
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onerro.summary: Function to call when the document fails to load properly.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onfocu.name: onfocus
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onfocu.summary: Function to call when the document receives focus.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onhash.name: onhashchange
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onhash.summary: Function to call when the fragment identifier part (starting with the hash (`'#'`) character) of the document's current address has changed.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onlang.name: onlanguagechange
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onlang.summary: Function to call when the preferred languages changed.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onload.name: onload
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onload.summary: Function to call when the document has finished loading.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onmess.name: onmessage
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onmess.summary: Function to call when the document has received a message.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onoffl.name: onoffline
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onoffl.summary: Function to call when network communication has failed.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/ononli.name: ononline
/web/html/element/body/attributes/ononli.summary: Function to call when network communication has been restored.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onpops.name: onpopstate
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onpops.summary: Function to call when the user has navigated session history.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onredo.name: onredo
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onredo.summary: Function to call when the user has moved forward in undo transaction history.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onresi.name: onresize
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onresi.summary: Function to call when the document has been resized.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onstor.name: onstorage
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onstor.summary: Function to call when the storage area has changed.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onundo.name: onundo
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onundo.summary: Function to call when the user has moved backward in undo transaction history.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/onunlo.name: onunload
/web/html/element/body/attributes/onunlo.summary: Function to call when the document is going away.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/rightm.name: rightmargin
/web/html/element/body/attributes/rightm.summary: The margin of the right of the body.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/topmar.name: topmargin
/web/html/element/body/attributes/topmar.summary: The margin of the top of the body.

/web/html/element/body/attributes/vlink.name: vlink
/web/html/element/body/attributes/vlink.summary: Color of text for visited hypertext links.

/web/html/element/br.name: br
/web/html/element/br.summary:
The `
` HTML element produces a line break in text (carriage-return). It is useful for writing a poem or an address, where the division of lines is significant.

/web/html/element/button.name: button
/web/html/element/button.summary: The `<button>` HTML element is an interactive element activated by a user with a mouse, keyboard, finger, voice command, or other assistive technology. Once activated, it then performs a programmable action, such as submitting a form or opening a dialog.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/auto.name: autofocus
/web/html/element/button/attributes/auto.summary: This Boolean attribute specifies that the button should have input focus when the page loads. Only one element in a document can have this attribute.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/auto.name: autocomplete
/web/html/element/button/attributes/auto.summary: This attribute on a button is nonstandard and Firefox-specific. Unlike other browsers, Firefox persists the dynamic disabled state of a button across page loads. Setting `autocomplete="off"` on the button disables this feature; see .

/web/html/element/button/attributes/disa.name: disabled
/web/html/element/button/attributes/disa.summary: This Boolean attribute prevents the user from interacting with the button: it cannot be pressed or focused.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.name: form
/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.summary: The form element to associate the button with (its form owner). The value of this attribute must be the `id` of a `<form>` in the same document. (If this attribute is not set, the `<button>` is associated with its ancestor `<form>` element, if any.)

/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.name: formaction
/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.summary: The URL that processes the information submitted by the button. Overrides the form attribute of the button's form owner. Does nothing if there is no form owner.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.name: formenctype
/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.summary: If the button is a submit button (it's inside/associated with a `<form>` and doesn't have `type="button"`), specifies how to encode the form data that is submitted. Possible values.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.name: formmethod
/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.summary: If the button is a submit button (it's inside/associated with a `<form>` and doesn't have `type="button"`), this attribute specifies the HTTP method used to submit the form. Possible values.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.name: formnovalidate
/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.summary: If the button is a submit button, this Boolean attribute specifies that the form is not to be validated when it is submitted. If this attribute is specified, it overrides the form attribute of the button's form owner.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.name: formtarget
/web/html/element/button/attributes/form.summary: If the button is a submit button, this attribute is an author-defined name or standardized, underscore-prefixed keyword indicating where to display the response from submitting the form. This is the `name` of, or keyword for, a browsing context (a tab, window, or iframe). If this attribute is specified, it overrides the target attribute of the button's form owner. The following keywords have special meanings.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/button/attributes/name.summary: The name of the button, submitted as a pair with the button's `value` as part of the form data, when that button is used to submit the form.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/button/attributes/type.summary: The default behavior of the button. Possible values are.

/web/html/element/button/attributes/valu.name: value
/web/html/element/button/attributes/valu.summary: Defines the value associated with the button's `name` when it's submitted with the form data. This value is passed to the server in params when the form is submitted using this button.

/web/html/element/canvas.name: canvas
/web/html/element/canvas.summary: Use the HTML `<canvas>` element with either the canvas scripting API or the WebGL API to draw graphics and animations.

/web/html/element/canvas/attributes/heig.name: height
/web/html/element/canvas/attributes/heig.summary: The height of the coordinate space in CSS pixels. Defaults to 150.

/web/html/element/canvas/attributes/moz-.name: moz-opaque
/web/html/element/canvas/attributes/moz-.summary: Lets the canvas know whether or not translucency will be a factor. If the canvas knows there's no translucency, painting performance can be optimized. This is only supported by Mozilla-based browsers; use the standardized {{domxref("HTMLCanvasElement.getContext()", "canvas.getContext('2d', { alpha: false })")}} instead.

/web/html/element/canvas/attributes/widt.name: width
/web/html/element/canvas/attributes/widt.summary: The width of the coordinate space in CSS pixels. Defaults to 300.

/web/html/element/caption.name: caption
/web/html/element/caption.summary: The `<caption>` HTML element specifies the caption (or title) of a table.

/web/html/element/center.name: center
/web/html/element/center.summary: The `<center>` HTML element is a block-level element that displays its block-level or inline contents centered horizontally within its containing element. The container is usually, but isn't required to be, body.

/web/html/element/cite.name: cite
/web/html/element/cite.summary: The `<cite>` HTML element is used to describe a reference to a cited creative work, and must include the title of that work. The reference may be in an abbreviated form according to context-appropriate conventions related to citation metadata.

/web/html/element/code.name: code
/web/html/element/code.summary: The `<code>` HTML element displays its contents styled in a fashion intended to indicate that the text is a short fragment of computer code. By default, the content text is displayed using the user agent default monospace font.

/web/html/element/col.name: col
/web/html/element/col.summary: The `<col>` HTML element defines a column within a table and is used for defining common semantics on all common cells. It is generally found within a colgroup element.

/web/html/element/col/attributes/span.name: span
/web/html/element/col/attributes/span.summary: This attribute contains a positive integer indicating the number of consecutive columns the `<col>` element spans. If not present, its default value is `1`.

/web/html/element/colgroup.name: colgroup
/web/html/element/colgroup.summary: The `<colgroup>` HTML element defines a group of columns within a table.

/web/html/element/colgroup/attributes/sp.name: span
/web/html/element/colgroup/attributes/sp.summary: This attribute contains a positive integer indicating the number of consecutive columns the `<colgroup>` element spans. If not present, its default value is `1`.

/web/html/element/content.name: content
/web/html/element/content.summary: The `<content>` HTML elementan obsolete part of the Web Components suite of technologieswas used inside of Shadow DOM as an insertion point, and wasn't meant to be used in ordinary HTML. It has now been replaced by the slot element, which creates a point in the DOM at which a shadow DOM can be inserted.

/web/html/element/data.name: data
/web/html/element/data.summary: The `<data>` HTML element links a given piece of content with a machine-readable translation. If the content is time- or date-related, the time element must be used.

/web/html/element/data/attributes/value.name: value
/web/html/element/data/attributes/value.summary: This attribute specifies the machine-readable translation of the content of the element.

/web/html/element/datalist.name: datalist
/web/html/element/datalist.summary: The `<datalist>` HTML element contains a set of option elements that represent the permissible or recommended options available to choose from within other controls.

/web/html/element/dd.name: dd
/web/html/element/dd.summary: The `<dd>` HTML element provides the description, definition, or value for the preceding term (dt) in a description list (dl).

/web/html/element/dd/attributes/nowrap.name: nowrap
/web/html/element/dd/attributes/nowrap.summary: If the value of this attribute is set to `yes`, the definition text will not wrap. The default value is `no`.

/web/html/element/del.name: del
/web/html/element/del.summary: The `<del>` HTML element represents a range of text that has been deleted from a document. This can be used when rendering "track changes" or source code diff information, for example. The ins element can be used for the opposite purpose: to indicate text that has been added to the document.

/web/html/element/del/attributes/cite.name: cite
/web/html/element/del/attributes/cite.summary: A URI for a resource that explains the change (for example, meeting minutes).

/web/html/element/del/attributes/datetim.name: datetime
/web/html/element/del/attributes/datetim.summary: This attribute indicates the time and date of the change and must be a valid date string with an optional time. If the value cannot be parsed as a date with an optional time string, the element does not have an associated time stamp. For the format of the string without a time, see Date strings. The format of the string if it includes both date and time is covered in Local date and time strings.

/web/html/element/details.name: details
/web/html/element/details.summary: The `<details>` HTML element creates a disclosure widget in which information is visible only when the widget is toggled into an "open" state. A summary or label must be provided using the summary element.

/web/html/element/details/attributes/ope.name: open
/web/html/element/details/attributes/ope.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates whether or not the details  that is, the contents of the `<details>` element  are currently visible. The details are shown when this attribute exists, or hidden when this attribute is absent. By default this attribute is absent which means the details are not visible.

/web/html/element/dfn.name: dfn
/web/html/element/dfn.summary: The `<dfn>` HTML element is used to indicate the term being defined within the context of a definition phrase or sentence. The p element, the dt/dd pairing, or the section element which is the nearest ancestor of the `<dfn>` is considered to be the definition of the term.

/web/html/element/dialog.name: dialog
/web/html/element/dialog.summary: The `<dialog>` HTML element represents a dialog box or other interactive component, such as a dismissible alert, inspector, or subwindow.

/web/html/element/dialog/attributes/open.name: open
/web/html/element/dialog/attributes/open.summary: Indicates that the dialog is active and can be interacted with. When the `open` attribute is not set, the dialog shouldn't be shown to the user.

/web/html/element/dir.name: dir
/web/html/element/dir.summary: The `<dir>` HTML element is used as a container for a directory of files and/or folders, potentially with styles and icons applied by the user agent. Do not use this obsolete element; instead, you should use the ul element for lists, including lists of files.

/web/html/element/dir/attributes/compact.name: compact
/web/html/element/dir/attributes/compact.summary: This Boolean attribute hints that the list should be rendered in a compact style. The interpretation of this attribute depends on the user agent and it doesn't work in all browsers.

/web/html/element/div.name: div
/web/html/element/div.summary: The `<div>` HTML element is the generic container for flow content. It has no effect on the content or layout until styled in some way using CSS (e.g. styling is directly applied to it, or some kind of layout model like Flexbox is applied to its parent element).

/web/html/element/dl.name: dl
/web/html/element/dl.summary: The `<dl>` HTML element represents a description list. The element encloses a list of groups of terms (specified using the dt element) and descriptions (provided by dd elements). Common uses for this element are to implement a glossary or to display metadata (a list of key-value pairs).

/web/html/element/dt.name: dt
/web/html/element/dt.summary: The `<dt>` HTML element specifies a term in a description or definition list, and as such must be used inside a dl element. It is usually followed by a dd element; however, multiple `<dt>` elements in a row indicate several terms that are all defined by the immediate next dd element.

/web/html/element/em.name: em
/web/html/element/em.summary: The `<em>` HTML element marks text that has stress emphasis. The `<em>` element can be nested, with each level of nesting indicating a greater degree of emphasis.

/web/html/element/embed.name: embed
/web/html/element/embed.summary: The `<embed>` HTML element embeds external content at the specified point in the document. This content is provided by an external application or other source of interactive content such as a browser plug-in.

/web/html/element/embed/attributes/heigh.name: height
/web/html/element/embed/attributes/heigh.summary: The displayed height of the resource, in CSS pixels. This must be an absolute value; percentages are not allowed.

/web/html/element/embed/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/embed/attributes/src.summary: The URL of the resource being embedded.

/web/html/element/embed/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/embed/attributes/type.summary: The MIME type to use to select the plug-in to instantiate.

/web/html/element/embed/attributes/width.name: width
/web/html/element/embed/attributes/width.summary: The displayed width of the resource, in CSS pixels. This must be an absolute value; percentages are not allowed.

/web/html/element/fieldset.name: fieldset
/web/html/element/fieldset.summary: The `<fieldset>` HTML element is used to group several controls as well as labels (label) within a web form.

/web/html/element/fieldset/attributes/di.name: disabled
/web/html/element/fieldset/attributes/di.summary: If this Boolean attribute is set, all form controls that are descendants of the `<fieldset>`, are disabled, meaning they are not editable and won't be submitted along with the form. They won't receive any browsing events, like mouse clicks or focus-related events. By default browsers display such controls grayed out. Note that form elements inside the legend element won't be disabled.

/web/html/element/fieldset/attributes/fo.name: form
/web/html/element/fieldset/attributes/fo.summary: This attribute takes the value of the id attribute of a form element you want the `<fieldset>` to be part of, even if it is not inside the form. Please note that usage of this is confusing  if you want the input elements inside the `<fieldset>` to be associated with the form, you need to use the `form` attribute directly on those elements. You can check which elements are associated with a form via JavaScript, using HTMLFormElement.elements.

/web/html/element/fieldset/attributes/na.name: name
/web/html/element/fieldset/attributes/na.summary: The name associated with the group.

/web/html/element/figcaption.name: figcaption
/web/html/element/figcaption.summary: The `<figcaption>` HTML element represents a caption or legend describing the rest of the contents of its parent figure element.

/web/html/element/figure.name: figure
/web/html/element/figure.summary: The `<figure>` HTML element represents self-contained content, potentially with an optional caption, which is specified using the figcaption element. The figure, its caption, and its contents are referenced as a single unit.

/web/html/element/font.name: font
/web/html/element/font.summary: The `<font>` HTML element defines the font size, color and face for its content.

/web/html/element/font/attributes/color.name: color
/web/html/element/font/attributes/color.summary: This attribute sets the text color using either a named color or a color specified in the hexadecimal #RRGGBB format.

/web/html/element/font/attributes/face.name: face
/web/html/element/font/attributes/face.summary: This attribute contains a comma-separated list of one or more font names. The document text in the default style is rendered in the first font face that the client's browser supports. If no font listed is installed on the local system, the browser typically defaults to the proportional or fixed-width font for that system.

/web/html/element/font/attributes/size.name: size
/web/html/element/font/attributes/size.summary: This attribute specifies the font size as either a numeric or relative value. Numeric values range from `1` to `7` with `1` being the smallest and `3` the default. It can be defined using a relative value, like `+2` or `-3`, which set it relative to the value of the size attribute of the basefont element, or relative to `3`, the default value, if none does exist.

/web/html/element/footer.name: footer
/web/html/element/footer.summary: The `<footer>` HTML element represents a footer for its nearest ancestor sectioning content or sectioning root element. A `<footer>` typically contains information about the author of the section, copyright data or links to related documents.

/web/html/element/form.name: form
/web/html/element/form.summary: The `<form>` HTML element represents a document section containing interactive controls for submitting information.

/web/html/element/form/attributes/accept.name: accept
/web/html/element/form/attributes/accept.summary: Comma-separated content types the server accepts.

/web/html/element/form/attributes/accept.name: accept-charset
/web/html/element/form/attributes/accept.summary: Space-separated character encoding the server accepts. The browser uses them in the order in which they are listed. The default value means the same encoding as the page.

/web/html/element/form/attributes/autoca.name: autocapitalize
/web/html/element/form/attributes/autoca.summary: A nonstandard attribute used by iOS Safari that controls how textual form elements should be automatically capitalized. `autocapitalize` attributes on a form elements override it on `<form>`. Possible values.

/web/html/element/form/attributes/autoco.name: autocomplete
/web/html/element/form/attributes/autoco.summary: Indicates whether input elements can by default have their values automatically completed by the browser. `autocomplete` attributes on form elements override it on `<form>`. Possible values.

/web/html/element/form/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/form/attributes/name.summary: The name of the form. The value must not be the empty string, and must be unique among the `form` elements in the forms collection that it is in, if any.

/web/html/element/form/attributes/rel.name: rel
/web/html/element/form/attributes/rel.summary: Creates a hyperlink or annotation depending on the value, see the `rel` attribute for details.

/web/html/element/frame.name: frame
/web/html/element/frame.summary: The `<frame>` HTML element defines a particular area in which another HTML document can be displayed. A frame should be used within a frameset.

/web/html/element/frame/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/frame/attributes/src.summary: This attribute specifies the document that will be displayed by the frame.

/web/html/element/frame/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/frame/attributes/name.summary: This attribute is used for labeling frames. Without labeling, every link will open in the frame that it's in  the closest parent frame. See the a attribute for more information.

/web/html/element/frame/attributes/nores.name: noresize
/web/html/element/frame/attributes/nores.summary: This attribute prevents resizing of frames by users.

/web/html/element/frame/attributes/scrol.name: scrolling
/web/html/element/frame/attributes/scrol.summary: This attribute defines the existence of a scrollbar. If this attribute is not used, the browser adds a scrollbar when necessary. There are two choices: "yes" for forcing a scrollbar even when it is not necessary and "no" for forcing no scrollbar even when it is necessary.

/web/html/element/frame/attributes/margi.name: marginheight
/web/html/element/frame/attributes/margi.summary: This attribute defines the height of the margin between frames.

/web/html/element/frame/attributes/margi.name: marginwidth
/web/html/element/frame/attributes/margi.summary: This attribute defines the width of the margin between frames.

/web/html/element/frame/attributes/frame.name: frameborder
/web/html/element/frame/attributes/frame.summary: This attribute allows you to specify a frame's border.

/web/html/element/frameset.name: frameset
/web/html/element/frameset.summary: The `<frameset>` HTML element is used to contain frame elements.

/web/html/element/frameset/attributes/co.name: cols
/web/html/element/frameset/attributes/co.summary: This attribute specifies the number and size of horizontal spaces in a frameset.

/web/html/element/frameset/attributes/ro.name: rows
/web/html/element/frameset/attributes/ro.summary: This attribute specifies the number and size of vertical spaces in a frameset.

/web/html/element/head.name: head
/web/html/element/head.summary: The `<head>` HTML element contains machine-readable information (metadata) about the document, like its title, scripts, and style sheets.

/web/html/element/head/attributes/profil.name: profile
/web/html/element/head/attributes/profil.summary: The URIs of one or more metadata profiles, separated by whitespace.

/web/html/element/header.name: header
/web/html/element/header.summary: The `<header>` HTML element represents introductory content, typically a group of introductory or navigational aids. It may contain some heading elements but also a logo, a search form, an author name, and other elements.

/web/html/element/h1.name: h6
/web/html/element/h1.summary: The `<h1>` to `<h6>` HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. `<h1>` is the highest section level and `<h6>` is the lowest.

/web/html/element/h2.name: h6
/web/html/element/h2.summary: The `<h1>` to `<h6>` HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. `<h1>` is the highest section level and `<h6>` is the lowest.

/web/html/element/h3.name: h6
/web/html/element/h3.summary: The `<h1>` to `<h6>` HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. `<h1>` is the highest section level and `<h6>` is the lowest.

/web/html/element/h4.name: h6
/web/html/element/h4.summary: The `<h1>` to `<h6>` HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. `<h1>` is the highest section level and `<h6>` is the lowest.

/web/html/element/h5.name: h6
/web/html/element/h5.summary: The `<h1>` to `<h6>` HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. `<h1>` is the highest section level and `<h6>` is the lowest.

/web/html/element/h6.name: h6
/web/html/element/h6.summary: The `<h1>` to `<h6>` HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. `<h1>` is the highest section level and `<h6>` is the lowest.

/web/html/element/hgroup.name: hgroup
/web/html/element/hgroup.summary: Warning: `<hgroup>` should not be used because no assistive technology supports it, and as a result it has a detrimental effect on assistance for headings placed within it. > > For more information see the Usage notes below.

/web/html/element/hr.name: hr
/web/html/element/hr.summary: The `<hr>` HTML element represents a thematic break between paragraph-level elements: for example, a change of scene in a story, or a shift of topic within a section.

/web/html/element/hr/attributes/align.name: align
/web/html/element/hr/attributes/align.summary: Sets the alignment of the rule on the page. If no value is specified, the default value is `left`.

/web/html/element/hr/attributes/color.name: color
/web/html/element/hr/attributes/color.summary: Sets the color of the rule through color name or hexadecimal value.

/web/html/element/hr/attributes/noshade.name: noshade
/web/html/element/hr/attributes/noshade.summary: Sets the rule to have no shading.

/web/html/element/hr/attributes/size.name: size
/web/html/element/hr/attributes/size.summary: Sets the height, in pixels, of the rule.

/web/html/element/hr/attributes/width.name: width
/web/html/element/hr/attributes/width.summary: Sets the length of the rule on the page through a pixel or percentage value.

/web/html/element/html.name: html
/web/html/element/html.summary: The `<html>` HTML element represents the root (top-level element) of an HTML document, so it is also referred to as the root element. All other elements must be descendants of this element.

/web/html/element/html/attributes/manife.name: manifest
/web/html/element/html/attributes/manife.summary: Specifies the URI of a resource manifest indicating resources that should be cached locally.

/web/html/element/html/attributes/versio.name: version
/web/html/element/html/attributes/versio.summary: Specifies the version of the HTML Doctype that governs the current document. This attribute is not needed, because it is redundant with the version information in the document type declaration.

/web/html/element/html/attributes/xmlns.name: xmlns
/web/html/element/html/attributes/xmlns.summary: Specifies the XML Namespace of the document. Default value is `"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"`. This is required in documents parsed with XML parser, and optional in text/html documents.

/web/html/element/i.name: i
/web/html/element/i.summary: The `<i>` HTML element represents a range of text that is set off from the normal text for some reason, such as idiomatic text, technical terms, taxonomical designations, among others. Historically, these have been presented using italicized type, which is the original source of the `<i>` naming of this element.

/web/html/element/iframe.name: iframe
/web/html/element/iframe.summary: The `<iframe>` HTML element represents a nested browsing context, embedding another HTML page into the current one.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/allo.name: allow
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/allo.summary: Specifies a feature policy for the `<iframe>`. The policy defines what features are available to the `<iframe>` based on the origin of the request (e.g. access to the microphone, camera, battery, web-share API, etc.).

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/allo.name: allowfullscreen
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/allo.summary: Set to `true` if the `<iframe>` can activate fullscreen mode by calling the Element.requestFullscreen method.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/allo.name: allowpaymentrequest
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/allo.summary: Set to `true` if a cross-origin `<iframe>` should be allowed to invoke the Payment Request API.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/csp.name: csp
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/csp.summary: A Content Security Policy enforced for the embedded resource. See HTMLIFrameElement.csp for details.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/fetc.name: fetchpriority
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/fetc.summary: Provides a hint of the relative priority to use when fetching the iframe document. Allowed values.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/heig.name: height
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/heig.summary: The height of the frame in CSS pixels. Default is `150`.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/load.name: loading
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/load.summary: Indicates how the browser should load the iframe.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/name.summary: A targetable name for the embedded browsing context. This can be used in the `target` attribute of the a, form, or base elements; the `formtarget` attribute of the input or button elements; or the `windowName` parameter in the window.open() method.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/refe.name: referrerpolicy
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/refe.summary: Indicates which referrer to send when fetching the frame's resource.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/sand.name: sandbox
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/sand.summary: Applies extra restrictions to the content in the frame. The value of the attribute can either be empty to apply all restrictions, or space-separated tokens to lift particular restrictions.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/src.summary: The URL of the page to embed. Use a value of `about:blank` to embed an empty page that conforms to the same-origin policy. Also note that programmatically removing an `<iframe>`'s src attribute (e.g. via Element.removeAttribute()) causes `about:blank` to be loaded in the frame in Firefox (from version 65), Chromium-based browsers, and Safari/iOS.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/srcd.name: srcdoc
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/srcd.summary: Inline HTML to embed, overriding the `src` attribute. If a browser does not support the `srcdoc` attribute, it will fall back to the URL in the `src` attribute.

/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/widt.name: width
/web/html/element/iframe/attributes/widt.summary: The width of the frame in CSS pixels. Default is `300`.

/web/html/element/image.name: image
/web/html/element/image.summary: The `<image>` HTML element is an ancient and poorly supported precursor to the img element. It should not be used.

/web/html/element/img.name: img
/web/html/element/img.summary: The `` HTML element embeds an image into the document.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/alt.name: alt
/web/html/element/img/attributes/alt.summary: Defines an alternative text description of the image.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/crossor.name: crossorigin
/web/html/element/img/attributes/crossor.summary: Indicates if the fetching of the image must be done using a CORS request. Image data from a CORS-enabled image returned from a CORS request can be reused in the canvas element without being marked "tainted".

/web/html/element/img/attributes/decodin.name: decoding
/web/html/element/img/attributes/decodin.summary: Provides an image decoding hint to the browser. Allowed values.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/fetchpr.name: fetchpriority
/web/html/element/img/attributes/fetchpr.summary: Provides a hint of the relative priority to use when fetching the image. Allowed values.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/height.name: height
/web/html/element/img/attributes/height.summary: The intrinsic height of the image, in pixels. Must be an integer without a unit.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/ismap.name: ismap
