/web/html/element/img/attributes/ismap.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates that the image is part of a server-side map. If so, the coordinates where the user clicked on the image are sent to the server.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/loading.name: loading
/web/html/element/img/attributes/loading.summary: Indicates how the browser should load the image.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/referre.name: referrerpolicy
/web/html/element/img/attributes/referre.summary: A string indicating which referrer to use when fetching the resource.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/sizes.name: sizes
/web/html/element/img/attributes/sizes.summary: One or more strings separated by commas, indicating a set of source sizes. Each source size consists of.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/img/attributes/src.summary: The image URL. Mandatory for the `` element. On Browser supporting `srcset`, `src` is treated like a candidate image with a pixel density descriptor `1x`, unless an image with this pixel density descriptor is already defined in `srcset`, or unless `srcset` contains `w` descriptors.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/srcset.name: srcset
/web/html/element/img/attributes/srcset.summary: One or more strings separated by commas, indicating possible image sources for the user agent to use. Each string is composed of.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/width.name: width
/web/html/element/img/attributes/width.summary: The intrinsic width of the image in pixels. Must be an integer without a unit.

/web/html/element/img/attributes/usemap.name: usemap
/web/html/element/img/attributes/usemap.summary: The partial URL (starting with `#`) of an image map associated with the element.

/web/html/element/input.name: input
/web/html/element/input.summary: The `<input>` HTML element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent. The `<input>` element is one of the most powerful and complex in all of HTML due to the sheer number of combinations of input types and attributes.

/web/html/element/ins.name: ins
/web/html/element/ins.summary: The `<ins>` HTML element represents a range of text that has been added to a document. You can use the del element to similarly represent a range of text that has been deleted from the document.

/web/html/element/ins/attributes/cite.name: cite
/web/html/element/ins/attributes/cite.summary: This attribute defines the URI of a resource that explains the change, such as a link to meeting minutes or a ticket in a troubleshooting system.

/web/html/element/ins/attributes/datetim.name: datetime
/web/html/element/ins/attributes/datetim.summary: This attribute indicates the time and date of the change and must be a valid date with an optional time string. If the value cannot be parsed as a date with an optional time string, the element does not have an associated time stamp. For the format of the string without a time, see Format of a valid date string. The format of the string if it includes both date and time is covered in Format of a valid local date and time string.

/web/html/element/kbd.name: kbd
/web/html/element/kbd.summary: The `<kbd>` HTML element represents a span of inline text denoting textual user input from a keyboard, voice input, or any other text entry device. By convention, the user agent defaults to rendering the contents of a `<kbd>` element using its default monospace font, although this is not mandated by the HTML standard.

/web/html/element/keygen.name: keygen
/web/html/element/keygen.summary: The `<keygen>` HTML element exists to facilitate generation of key material, and submission of the public key as part of an HTML form. This mechanism is designed for use with Web-based certificate management systems. It is expected that the `<keygen>` element will be used in an HTML form along with other information needed to construct a certificate request, and that the result of the process will be a signed certificate.

/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/auto.name: autofocus
/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/auto.summary: This Boolean attribute lets you specify that the control should have input focus when the page loads, unless the user overrides it, for example by typing in a different control. Only one form element in a document can have the `autofocus` attribute, which is a Boolean.

/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/chal.name: challenge
/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/chal.summary: A challenge string that is submitted along with the public key. Defaults to an empty string if not specified.

/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/disa.name: disabled
/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/disa.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates that the form control is not available for interaction.

/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/form.name: form
/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/form.summary: The form element that this element is associated with (its form owner). The value of the attribute must be an `id` of a form element in the same document. If this attribute is not specified, this element must be a descendant of a form element. This attribute enables you to place `<keygen>` elements anywhere within a document, not just as descendants of their form elements.

/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/keyt.name: keytype
/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/keyt.summary: The type of key generated. The default value is `RSA`.

/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/keygen/attributes/name.summary: The name of the control, which is submitted with the form data.

/web/html/element/label.name: label
/web/html/element/label.summary: The `<label>` HTML element represents a caption for an item in a user interface.

/web/html/element/legend.name: legend
/web/html/element/legend.summary: The `<legend>` HTML element represents a caption for the content of its parent fieldset.

/web/html/element/li.name: li
/web/html/element/li.summary: The `<li>` HTML element is used to represent an item in a list. It must be contained in a parent element: an ordered list (ol), an unordered list (ul), or a menu (menu). In menus and unordered lists, list items are usually displayed using bullet points. In ordered lists, they are usually displayed with an ascending counter on the left, such as a number or letter.

/web/html/element/li/attributes/value.name: value
/web/html/element/li/attributes/value.summary: This integer attribute indicates the current ordinal value of the list item as defined by the ol element. The only allowed value for this attribute is a number, even if the list is displayed with Roman numerals or letters. List items that follow this one continue numbering from the value set. The value attribute has no meaning for unordered lists (ul) or for menus (menu).

/web/html/element/li/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/li/attributes/type.summary: This character attribute indicates the numbering type.

/web/html/element/link.name: link
/web/html/element/link.summary: The `<link>` HTML element specifies relationships between the current document and an external resource. This element is most commonly used to link to CSS, but is also used to establish site icons (both "favicon" style icons and icons for the home screen and apps on mobile devices) among other things.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/as.name: as
/web/html/element/link/attributes/as.summary: This attribute is only used when `rel="preload"` or `rel="prefetch"` has been set on the `<link>` element.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/crosso.name: crossorigin
/web/html/element/link/attributes/crosso.summary: This enumerated attribute indicates whether CORS must be used when fetching the resource.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/disabl.name: disabled
/web/html/element/link/attributes/disabl.summary: For `rel="stylesheet"` only, the `disabled` Boolean attribute indicates whether or not the described stylesheet should be loaded and applied to the document.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/fetchp.name: fetchpriority
/web/html/element/link/attributes/fetchp.summary: Provides a hint of the relative priority to use when fetching a preloaded resource. Allowed values.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/href.name: href
/web/html/element/link/attributes/href.summary: This attribute specifies the URL of the linked resource. A URL can be absolute or relative.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/hrefla.name: hreflang
/web/html/element/link/attributes/hrefla.summary: This attribute indicates the language of the linked resource.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/images.name: imagesizes
/web/html/element/link/attributes/images.summary: For `rel="preload"` and `as="image"` only, the `imagesizes` attribute is a sizes attribute that indicates to preload the appropriate resource used by an `img` element with corresponding values for its `srcset` and `sizes` attributes.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/images.name: imagesrcset
/web/html/element/link/attributes/images.summary: For `rel="preload"` and `as="image"` only, the `imagesrcset` attribute is a sourceset attribute that indicates to preload the appropriate resource used by an `img` element with corresponding values for its `srcset` and `sizes` attributes.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/integr.name: integrity
/web/html/element/link/attributes/integr.summary: Contains inline metadata  a base64-encoded cryptographic hash of the resource (file) you're telling the browser to fetch.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/media.name: media
/web/html/element/link/attributes/media.summary: This attribute specifies the media that the linked resource applies to. Its value must be a media type / media query.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/prefet.name: prefetch
/web/html/element/link/attributes/prefet.summary: Identifies a resource that might be required by the next navigation and that the user agent should retrieve it.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/referr.name: referrerpolicy
/web/html/element/link/attributes/referr.summary: A string indicating which referrer to use when fetching the resource.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/rel.name: rel
/web/html/element/link/attributes/rel.summary: This attribute names a relationship of the linked document to the current document. The attribute must be a space-separated list of link type values.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/sizes.name: sizes
/web/html/element/link/attributes/sizes.summary: This attribute defines the sizes of the icons for visual media contained in the resource.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/title.name: title
/web/html/element/link/attributes/title.summary: The `title` attribute has special semantics on the `<link>` element.

/web/html/element/link/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/link/attributes/type.summary: This attribute is used to define the type of the content linked to.

/web/html/element/main.name: main
/web/html/element/main.summary: The `<main>` HTML element represents the dominant content of the body of a document. The main content area consists of content that is directly related to or expands upon the central topic of a document, or the central functionality of an application.

/web/html/element/map.name: map
/web/html/element/map.summary: The `<map>` HTML element is used with area elements to define an image map (a clickable link area).

/web/html/element/map/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/map/attributes/name.summary: The `name` attribute gives the map a name so that it can be referenced. The attribute must be present and must have a non-empty value with no space characters. The value of the `name` attribute must not be equal to the value of the `name` attribute of another `<map>` element in the same document. If the id attribute is also specified, both attributes must have the same value.

/web/html/element/mark.name: mark
/web/html/element/mark.summary: The `<mark>` HTML element represents text which is marked or highlighted for reference or notation purposes, due to the marked passage's relevance or importance in the enclosing context.

/web/html/element/marquee.name: marquee
/web/html/element/marquee.summary: The `<marquee>` HTML element is used to insert a scrolling area of text. You can control what happens when the text reaches the edges of its content area using its attributes.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/beh.name: behavior
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/beh.summary: Sets how the text is scrolled within the marquee. Possible values are `scroll`, `slide` and `alternate`. If no value is specified, the default value is `scroll`.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/bgc.name: bgcolor
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/bgc.summary: Sets the background color through color name or hexadecimal value.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/dir.name: direction
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/dir.summary: Sets the direction of the scrolling within the marquee. Possible values are `left`, `right`, `up` and `down`. If no value is specified, the default value is `left`.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/hei.name: height
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/hei.summary: Sets the height in pixels or percentage value.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/loo.name: loop
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/loo.summary: Sets the number of times the marquee will scroll. If no value is specified, the default value is 1, which means the marquee will scroll continuously.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/scr.name: scrollamount
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/scr.summary: Sets the amount of scrolling at each interval in pixels. The default value is 6.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/scr.name: scrolldelay
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/scr.summary: Sets the interval between each scroll movement in milliseconds. The default value is 85. Note that any value smaller than 60 is ignored and the value 60 is used instead, unless`truespeed`is specified.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/tru.name: truespeed
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/tru.summary: By default,`scrolldelay`values lower than 60 are ignored. If`truespeed`is present, those values are not ignored.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/vsp.name: vspace
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/vsp.summary: Sets the vertical margin in pixels or percentage value.

/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/wid.name: width
/web/html/element/marquee/attributes/wid.summary: Sets the width in pixels or percentage value.

/web/html/element/menu.name: menu
/web/html/element/menu.summary: The `<menu>` HTML element is a semantic alternative to ul. It represents an unordered list of items (represented by li elements), each of which represents a link or other command that the user can activate.

/web/html/element/menuitem.name: menuitem
/web/html/element/menuitem.summary: The `<menuitem>` HTML element represents a command that a user is able to invoke through a popup menu. This includes context menus, as well as menus that might be attached to a menu button.

/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/ch.name: checked
/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/ch.summary: Boolean attribute which indicates whether the command is selected. May only be used when the `type` attribute is `checkbox` or `radio`.

/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/co.name: command
/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/co.summary: Specifies the ID of a separate element, indicating a command to be invoked indirectly. May not be used within a menu item that also includes the attributes `checked`, `disabled`, `icon`, `label`, `radiogroup` or `type`.

/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/de.name: default
/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/de.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates use of the same command as the menu's subject element (such as a `button` or `input`).

/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/di.name: disabled
/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/di.summary: Boolean attribute which indicates that the command is not available in the current state. Note that `disabled` is distinct from `hidden`; the `disabled` attribute is appropriate in any context where a change in circumstances might render the command relevant.

/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/ic.name: icon
/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/ic.summary: Image URL, used to provide a picture to represent the command.

/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/la.name: label
/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/la.summary: The name of the command as shown to the user. Required when a `command` attribute is not present.

/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/ra.name: radiogroup
/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/ra.summary: This attribute specifies the name of a group of commands to be toggled as radio buttons when selected. May only be used where the `type` attribute is `radio`.

/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/ty.name: type
/web/html/element/menuitem/attributes/ty.summary: This attribute indicates the kind of command, and can be one of three values.

/web/html/element/meta.name: meta
/web/html/element/meta.summary: The `<meta>` HTML element represents metadata that cannot be represented by other HTML meta-related elements, like base, link, script, style or title.

/web/html/element/meta/attributes/charse.name: charset
/web/html/element/meta/attributes/charse.summary: This attribute declares the document's character encoding. If the attribute is present, its value must be an ASCII case-insensitive match for the string "`utf-8`", because UTF-8 is the only valid encoding for HTML5 documents. `<meta>` elements which declare a character encoding must be located entirely within the first 1024 bytes of the document.

/web/html/element/meta/attributes/conten.name: content
/web/html/element/meta/attributes/conten.summary: This attribute contains the value for the http-equiv or name attribute, depending on which is used.

/web/html/element/meta/attributes/http-e.name: http-equiv
/web/html/element/meta/attributes/http-e.summary: Defines a pragma directive. The attribute is named `http-equiv(alent)` because all the allowed values are names of particular HTTP headers.

/web/html/element/meter.name: meter
/web/html/element/meter.summary: The `<meter>` HTML element represents either a scalar value within a known range or a fractional value.

/web/html/element/meter/attributes/value.name: value
/web/html/element/meter/attributes/value.summary: The current numeric value. This must be between the minimum and maximum values (`min` attribute and `max` attribute) if they are specified. If unspecified or malformed, the value is `0`. If specified, but not within the range given by the `min` attribute and `max` attribute, the value is equal to the nearest end of the range.

/web/html/element/meter/attributes/min.name: min
/web/html/element/meter/attributes/min.summary: The lower numeric bound of the measured range. This must be less than the maximum value (`max` attribute), if specified. If unspecified, the minimum value is `0`.

/web/html/element/meter/attributes/max.name: max
/web/html/element/meter/attributes/max.summary: The upper numeric bound of the measured range. This must be greater than the minimum value (`min` attribute), if specified. If unspecified, the maximum value is `1`.

/web/html/element/meter/attributes/low.name: low
/web/html/element/meter/attributes/low.summary: The upper numeric bound of the low end of the measured range. This must be greater than the minimum value (`min` attribute), and it also must be less than the high value and maximum value (`high` attribute and `max` attribute, respectively), if any are specified. If unspecified, or if less than the minimum value, the `low` value is equal to the minimum value.

/web/html/element/meter/attributes/high.name: high
/web/html/element/meter/attributes/high.summary: The lower numeric bound of the high end of the measured range. This must be less than the maximum value (`max` attribute), and it also must be greater than the low value and minimum value (`low` attribute and `min` attribute, respectively), if any are specified. If unspecified, or if greater than the maximum value, the `high` value is equal to the maximum value.

/web/html/element/meter/attributes/optim.name: optimum
/web/html/element/meter/attributes/optim.summary: This attribute indicates the optimal numeric value. It must be within the range (as defined by the `min` attribute and `max` attribute). When used with the `low` attribute and `high` attribute, it gives an indication where along the range is considered preferable. For example, if it is between the `min` attribute and the `low` attribute, then the lower range is considered preferred. The browser may color the meter's bar differently depending on whether the value is less than or equal to the optimum value.

/web/html/element/nav.name: nav
/web/html/element/nav.summary: The `<nav>` HTML element represents a section of a page whose purpose is to provide navigation links, either within the current document or to other documents. Common examples of navigation sections are menus, tables of contents, and indexes.

/web/html/element/nobr.name: nobr
/web/html/element/nobr.summary: The `<nobr>` HTML element prevents the text it contains from automatically wrapping across multiple lines, potentially resulting in the user having to scroll horizontally to see the entire width of the text.

/web/html/element/noembed.name: noembed
/web/html/element/noembed.summary: The `<noembed>` HTML element is an obsolete, non-standard way to provide alternative, or "fallback", content for browsers that do not support the embed element or do not support the type of embedded content an author wishes to use. This element was deprecated in HTML 4.01 and above in favor of placing fallback content between the opening and closing tags of an object element.

/web/html/element/noframes.name: noframes
/web/html/element/noframes.summary: The `<noframes>` HTML element provides content to be presented in browsers that don't support (or have disabled support for) the frame element. Although most commonly-used browsers support frames, there are exceptions, including certain special-use browsers including some mobile browsers, as well as text-mode browsers.

/web/html/element/noscript.name: noscript
/web/html/element/noscript.summary: The `<noscript>` HTML element defines a section of HTML to be inserted if a script type on the page is unsupported or if scripting is currently turned off in the browser.

/web/html/element/object.name: object
/web/html/element/object.summary: The `<object>` HTML element represents an external resource, which can be treated as an image, a nested browsing context, or a resource to be handled by a plugin.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/arch.name: archive
/web/html/element/object/attributes/arch.summary: A space-separated list of URIs for archives of resources for the object.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/bord.name: border
/web/html/element/object/attributes/bord.summary: The width of a border around the control, in pixels.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/clas.name: classid
/web/html/element/object/attributes/clas.summary: The URI of the object's implementation. It can be used together with, or in place of, the data attribute.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/code.name: codebase
/web/html/element/object/attributes/code.summary: The base path used to resolve relative URIs specified by classid, data, or archive. If not specified, the default is the base URI of the current document.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/code.name: codetype
/web/html/element/object/attributes/code.summary: The content type of the data specified by classid.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/data.name: data
/web/html/element/object/attributes/data.summary: The address of the resource as a valid URL. At least one of data and type must be defined.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/decl.name: declare
/web/html/element/object/attributes/decl.summary: The presence of this Boolean attribute makes this element a declaration only. The object must be instantiated by a subsequent `<object>` element. In HTML5, repeat the <object> element completely each time that the resource is reused.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/form.name: form
/web/html/element/object/attributes/form.summary: The form element, if any, that the object element is associated with (its form owner). The value of the attribute must be an ID of a form element in the same document.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/heig.name: height
/web/html/element/object/attributes/heig.summary: The height of the displayed resource, in CSS pixels. -- (Absolute values only. NO percentages)

/web/html/element/object/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/object/attributes/name.summary: The name of valid browsing context (HTML5), or the name of the control (HTML 4).

/web/html/element/object/attributes/stan.name: standby
/web/html/element/object/attributes/stan.summary: A message that the browser can show while loading the object's implementation and data.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/object/attributes/type.summary: The content type of the resource specified by data. At least one of data and type must be defined.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/usem.name: usemap
/web/html/element/object/attributes/usem.summary: A hash-name reference to a map element; that is a '#' followed by the value of a name of a map element.

/web/html/element/object/attributes/widt.name: width
/web/html/element/object/attributes/widt.summary: The width of the display resource, in CSS pixels. -- (Absolute values only. NO percentages)

/web/html/element/ol.name: ol
/web/html/element/ol.summary: The `<ol>` HTML element represents an ordered list of items  typically rendered as a numbered list.

/web/html/element/ol/attributes/reversed.name: reversed
/web/html/element/ol/attributes/reversed.summary: This Boolean attribute specifies that the list's items are in reverse order. Items will be numbered from high to low.

/web/html/element/ol/attributes/start.name: start
/web/html/element/ol/attributes/start.summary: An integer to start counting from for the list items. Always an Arabic numeral (1, 2, 3, etc.), even when the numbering `type` is letters or Roman numerals. For example, to start numbering elements from the letter "d" or the Roman numeral "iv," use `start="4"`.

/web/html/element/optgroup.name: optgroup
/web/html/element/optgroup.summary: The `<optgroup>` HTML element creates a grouping of options within a select element.

/web/html/element/optgroup/attributes/di.name: disabled
/web/html/element/optgroup/attributes/di.summary: If this Boolean attribute is set, none of the items in this option group is selectable. Often browsers grey out such control and it won't receive any browsing events, like mouse clicks or focus-related ones.

/web/html/element/optgroup/attributes/la.name: label
/web/html/element/optgroup/attributes/la.summary: The name of the group of options, which the browser can use when labeling the options in the user interface. This attribute is mandatory if this element is used.

/web/html/element/option.name: option
/web/html/element/option.summary: The `<option>` HTML element is used to define an item contained in a select, an optgroup, or a datalist element. As such, `<option>` can represent menu items in popups and other lists of items in an HTML document.

/web/html/element/option/attributes/disa.name: disabled
/web/html/element/option/attributes/disa.summary: If this Boolean attribute is set, this option is not checkable. Often browsers grey out such control and it won't receive any browsing event, like mouse clicks or focus-related ones. If this attribute is not set, the element can still be disabled if one of its ancestors is a disabled optgroup element.

/web/html/element/option/attributes/labe.name: label
/web/html/element/option/attributes/labe.summary: This attribute is text for the label indicating the meaning of the option. If the `label` attribute isn't defined, its value is that of the element text content.

/web/html/element/option/attributes/sele.name: selected
/web/html/element/option/attributes/sele.summary: If present, this Boolean attribute indicates that the option is initially selected. If the `<option>` element is the descendant of a select element whose multiple attribute is not set, only one single `<option>` of this select element may have the `selected` attribute.

/web/html/element/option/attributes/valu.name: value
/web/html/element/option/attributes/valu.summary: The content of this attribute represents the value to be submitted with the form, should this option be selected. If this attribute is omitted, the value is taken from the text content of the option element.

/web/html/element/output.name: output
/web/html/element/output.summary: The `<output>` HTML element is a container element into which a site or app can inject the results of a calculation or the outcome of a user action.

/web/html/element/output/attributes/for.name: for
/web/html/element/output/attributes/for.summary: A space-separated list of other elements' ids, indicating that those elements contributed input values to (or otherwise affected) the calculation.

/web/html/element/output/attributes/form.name: form
/web/html/element/output/attributes/form.summary: The form element to associate the output with (its form owner). The value of this attribute must be the id of a `<form>` in the same document. (If this attribute is not set, the `<output>` is associated with its ancestor `<form>` element, if any.)

/web/html/element/output/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/output/attributes/name.summary: The element's name. Used in the HTMLFormElement.elements API.

/web/html/element/p.name: p
/web/html/element/p.summary:
The `

` HTML element represents a paragraph. Paragraphs are usually represented in visual media as blocks of text separated from adjacent blocks by blank lines and/or first-line indentation, but HTML paragraphs can be any structural grouping of related content, such as images or form fields.

/web/html/element/param.name: param
/web/html/element/param.summary: The `<param>` HTML element defines parameters for an object element.

/web/html/element/param/attributes/value.name: value
/web/html/element/param/attributes/value.summary: Specifies the value of the parameter.

/web/html/element/param/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/param/attributes/type.summary: Only used if the `valuetype` is set to `ref`. Specifies the MIME type of values found at the URI specified by value.

/web/html/element/param/attributes/value.name: valuetype
/web/html/element/param/attributes/value.summary: Specifies the type of the `value` attribute. Possible values are.

/web/html/element/picture.name: picture
/web/html/element/picture.summary: The `<picture>` HTML element contains zero or more source elements and one img element to offer alternative versions of an image for different display/device scenarios.

/web/html/element/plaintext.name: plaintext
/web/html/element/plaintext.summary: The `<plaintext>` HTML element renders everything following the start tag as raw text, ignoring any following HTML. There is no closing tag, since everything after it is considered raw text.

/web/html/element/portal.name: portal
/web/html/element/portal.summary: The `<portal>` HTML element enables the embedding of another HTML page into the current one for the purposes of allowing smoother navigation into new pages.

/web/html/element/portal/attributes/refe.name: referrerpolicy
/web/html/element/portal/attributes/refe.summary: Sets the referrer policy to use when requesting the page at the URL given as the value of the `src` attribute.

/web/html/element/portal/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/portal/attributes/src.summary: The URL of the page to embed.

/web/html/element/pre.name: pre
/web/html/element/pre.summary: The `<pre>` HTML element represents preformatted text which is to be presented exactly as written in the HTML file. The text is typically rendered using a non-proportional, or monospaced, font. Whitespace inside this element is displayed as written.

/web/html/element/pre/attributes/cols.name: cols
/web/html/element/pre/attributes/cols.summary: Contains the preferred count of characters that a line should have. It was a non-standard synonym of width. To achieve such an effect, use CSS width instead.

/web/html/element/pre/attributes/width.name: width
/web/html/element/pre/attributes/width.summary: Contains the preferred count of characters that a line should have. Though technically still implemented, this attribute has no visual effect; to achieve such an effect, use CSS width instead.

/web/html/element/pre/attributes/wrap.name: wrap
/web/html/element/pre/attributes/wrap.summary: Is a hint indicating how the overflow must happen. In modern browser this hint is ignored and no visual effect results in its present; to achieve such an effect, use CSS white-space instead.

/web/html/element/progress.name: progress
/web/html/element/progress.summary: The `<progress>` HTML element displays an indicator showing the completion progress of a task, typically displayed as a progress bar.

/web/html/element/progress/attributes/ma.name: max
/web/html/element/progress/attributes/ma.summary: This attribute describes how much work the task indicated by the `progress` element requires. The `max` attribute, if present, must have a value greater than `0` and be a valid floating point number. The default value is `1`.

/web/html/element/progress/attributes/va.name: value
/web/html/element/progress/attributes/va.summary: This attribute specifies how much of the task that has been completed. It must be a valid floating point number between `0` and `max`, or between `0` and `1` if `max` is omitted. If there is no `value` attribute, the progress bar is indeterminate; this indicates that an activity is ongoing with no indication of how long it is expected to take.

/web/html/element/q.name: q
/web/html/element/q.summary: The `<q>` HTML element indicates that the enclosed text is a short inline quotation. Most modern browsers implement this by surrounding the text in quotation marks. This element is intended for short quotations that don't require paragraph breaks; for long quotations use the blockquote element.

/web/html/element/q/attributes/cite.name: cite
/web/html/element/q/attributes/cite.summary: The value of this attribute is a URL that designates a source document or message for the information quoted. This attribute is intended to point to information explaining the context or the reference for the quote.

/web/html/element/rb.name: rb
/web/html/element/rb.summary: The `<rb>` HTML element is used to delimit the base text component of a ruby annotation, i.e. the text that is being annotated. One `<rb>` element should wrap each separate atomic segment of the base text.

/web/html/element/rp.name: rp
/web/html/element/rp.summary: The `<rp>` HTML element is used to provide fall-back parentheses for browsers that do not support display of ruby annotations using the ruby element. One `<rp>` element should enclose each of the opening and closing parentheses that wrap the rt element that contains the annotation's text.

/web/html/element/rt.name: rt
/web/html/element/rt.summary: The `<rt>` HTML element specifies the ruby text component of a ruby annotation, which is used to provide pronunciation, translation, or transliteration information for East Asian typography. The `<rt>` element must always be contained within a ruby element.

/web/html/element/rtc.name: rtc
/web/html/element/rtc.summary: The `<rtc>` HTML element embraces semantic annotations of characters presented in a ruby of rb elements used inside of ruby element. rb elements can have both pronunciation (rt) and semantic (rtc) annotations.

/web/html/element/ruby.name: ruby
/web/html/element/ruby.summary: The `<ruby>` HTML element represents small annotations that are rendered above, below, or next to base text, usually used for showing the pronunciation of East Asian characters. It can also be used for annotating other kinds of text, but this usage is less common.

/web/html/element/s.name: s
/web/html/element/s.summary: The `<s>` HTML element renders text with a strikethrough, or a line through it. Use the `<s>` element to represent things that are no longer relevant or no longer accurate. However, `<s>` is not appropriate when indicating document edits; for that, use the del and ins elements, as appropriate.

/web/html/element/samp.name: samp
/web/html/element/samp.summary: The `<samp>` HTML element is used to enclose inline text which represents sample (or quoted) output from a computer program. Its contents are typically rendered using the browser's default monospaced font (such as wikipedia or Lucida Console).

/web/html/element/script.name: script
/web/html/element/script.summary: The `<script>` HTML element is used to embed executable code or data; this is typically used to embed or refer to JavaScript code. The `<script>` element can also be used with other languages, such as WebGL's GLSL shader programming language and JSON.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/asyn.name: async
/web/html/element/script/attributes/asyn.summary: For classic scripts, if the `async` attribute is present, then the classic script will be fetched in parallel to parsing and evaluated as soon as it is available.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/cros.name: crossorigin
/web/html/element/script/attributes/cros.summary: Normal `script` elements pass minimal information to the  for scripts which do not pass the standard CORS checks. To allow error logging for sites which use a separate domain for static media, use this attribute. See CORS settings attributes for a more descriptive explanation of its valid arguments.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/defe.name: defer
/web/html/element/script/attributes/defe.summary: This Boolean attribute is set to indicate to a browser that the script is meant to be executed after the document has been parsed, but before firing Document/DOMContentLoaded_event.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/fetc.name: fetchpriority
/web/html/element/script/attributes/fetc.summary: Provides a hint of the relative priority to use when fetching an external script. Allowed values.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/inte.name: integrity
/web/html/element/script/attributes/inte.summary: This attribute contains inline metadata that a user agent can use to verify that a fetched resource has been delivered free of unexpected manipulation. See Subresource Integrity.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/nomo.name: nomodule
/web/html/element/script/attributes/nomo.summary: This Boolean attribute is set to indicate that the script should not be executed in browsers that support ES2015 modules  in effect, this can be used to serve fallback scripts to older browsers that do not support modular JavaScript code.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/nonc.name: nonce
/web/html/element/script/attributes/nonc.summary: A cryptographic nonce (number used once) to allow scripts in a script-src Content-Security-Policy. The server must generate a unique nonce value each time it transmits a policy. It is critical to provide a nonce that cannot be guessed as bypassing a resource's policy is otherwise trivial.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/refe.name: referrerpolicy
/web/html/element/script/attributes/refe.summary: Indicates which referrer to send when fetching the script, or resources fetched by the script.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/script/attributes/src.summary: This attribute specifies the URI of an external script; this can be used as an alternative to embedding a script directly within a document.

/web/html/element/script/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/script/attributes/type.summary: This attribute indicates the type of script represented. The value of this attribute will be in one of the following categories.

/web/html/element/section.name: section
/web/html/element/section.summary: The `<section>` HTML element represents a generic standalone section of a document, which doesn't have a more specific semantic element to represent it. Sections should always have a heading, with very few exceptions.

/web/html/element/select.name: select
/web/html/element/select.summary: The `<select>` HTML element represents a control that provides a menu of options.

/web/html/element/select/attributes/auto.name: autocomplete
/web/html/element/select/attributes/auto.summary: A string providing a hint for a user agent autocomplete feature. See The HTML autocomplete attribute for a complete list of values and details on how to use autocomplete.

/web/html/element/select/attributes/auto.name: autofocus
/web/html/element/select/attributes/auto.summary: This Boolean attribute lets you specify that a form control should have input focus when the page loads. Only one form element in a document can have the `autofocus` attribute.

/web/html/element/select/attributes/disa.name: disabled
/web/html/element/select/attributes/disa.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates that the user cannot interact with the control. If this attribute is not specified, the control inherits its setting from the containing element, for example fieldset; if there is no containing element with the `disabled` attribute set, then the control is enabled.

/web/html/element/select/attributes/form.name: form
/web/html/element/select/attributes/form.summary: The form element to associate the `<select>` with (its form owner). The value of this attribute must be the id of a `<form>` in the same document. (If this attribute is not set, the `<select>` is associated with its ancestor `<form>` element, if any.)

/web/html/element/select/attributes/mult.name: multiple
/web/html/element/select/attributes/mult.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates that multiple options can be selected in the list. If it is not specified, then only one option can be selected at a time. When `multiple` is specified, most browsers will show a scrolling list box instead of a single line dropdown.

/web/html/element/select/attributes/name.name: name
/web/html/element/select/attributes/name.summary: This attribute is used to specify the name of the control.

/web/html/element/select/attributes/requ.name: required
/web/html/element/select/attributes/requ.summary: A Boolean attribute indicating that an option with a non-empty string value must be selected.

/web/html/element/select/attributes/size.name: size
/web/html/element/select/attributes/size.summary: If the control is presented as a scrolling list box (e.g. when `multiple` is specified), this attribute represents the number of rows in the list that should be visible at one time. Browsers are not required to present a select element as a scrolled list box. The default value is `0`.

/web/html/element/shadow.name: shadow
/web/html/element/shadow.summary: The `<shadow>` HTML elementan obsolete part of the Web Components technology suitewas intended to be used as a shadow DOM insertion point. You might have used it if you have created multiple shadow roots under a shadow host. It is not useful in ordinary HTML.

/web/html/element/slot.name: slot
/web/html/element/slot.summary: The `<slot>` HTML elementpart of the Web Components technology suiteis a placeholder inside a web component that you can fill with your own markup, which lets you create separate DOM trees and present them together.

/web/html/element/small.name: small
/web/html/element/small.summary: The `<small>` HTML element represents side-comments and small print, like copyright and legal text, independent of its styled presentation. By default, it renders text within it one font-size smaller, such as from `small` to `x-small`.

/web/html/element/source.name: source
/web/html/element/source.summary: The `<source>` HTML element specifies multiple media resources for the picture, the audio element, or the video element. It is an empty element, meaning that it has no content and does not have a closing tag. It is commonly used to offer the same media content in multiple file formats in order to provide compatibility with a broad range of browsers given their differing support for image file formats and media file formats.

/web/html/element/source/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/source/attributes/type.summary: The MIME media type of the resource, optionally with a `codecs` parameter.

/web/html/element/source/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/source/attributes/src.summary: Required if the `source` elements parent is an audio and video element, but not allowed if the `source` elements parent is a picture element.

/web/html/element/source/attributes/srcs.name: srcset
/web/html/element/source/attributes/srcs.summary: Required if the `source` elements parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` elements parent is an audio or video element.

/web/html/element/source/attributes/size.name: sizes
/web/html/element/source/attributes/size.summary: Allowed if the `source` elements parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` elements parent is an audio or video element.

/web/html/element/source/attributes/medi.name: media
/web/html/element/source/attributes/medi.summary: Allowed if the `source` elements parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` elements parent is an audio or video element.

/web/html/element/source/attributes/heig.name: height
/web/html/element/source/attributes/heig.summary: Allowed if the `source` elements parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` elements parent is an audio or video element.

/web/html/element/source/attributes/widt.name: width
/web/html/element/source/attributes/widt.summary: Allowed if the `source` elements parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` elements parent is an audio or video element.

/web/html/element/spacer.name: spacer
/web/html/element/spacer.summary: The `<spacer>` HTML element is an obsolete HTML element which allowed insertion of empty spaces on pages. It was devised by Netscape to accomplish the same effect as a single-pixel layout image, which was something web designers used to use to add white spaces to web pages without actually using an image. However, `<spacer>` no longer supported by any major browser and the same effects can now be achieved using simple CSS.

/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/type.summary: This attribute determines type of spacer. Possible values are `horizontal`, `vertical` and `block`.

/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/size.name: size
/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/size.summary: This attribute can be used for defining size of spacer in pixels when type is `horizontal` or `vertical`.

/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/widt.name: width
/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/widt.summary: This attribute can be used for defining width of spacer in pixels when type is `block`.

/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/heig.name: height
/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/heig.summary: This attribute can be used for defining height of spacer in pixels when type is `block`.

/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/alig.name: align
/web/html/element/spacer/attributes/alig.summary: This attribute determines alignment of spacer. Possible values are `left`, `right` and `center`.

/web/html/element/span.name: span
/web/html/element/span.summary: The `<span>` HTML element is a generic inline container for phrasing content, which does not inherently represent anything. It can be used to group elements for styling purposes (using the class or id attributes), or because they share attribute values, such as lang. It should be used only when no other semantic element is appropriate. `<span>` is very much like a div element, but div is a block-level element whereas a `<span>` is an inline element.

/web/html/element/strike.name: strike
/web/html/element/strike.summary: The `<strike>` HTML element places a strikethrough (horizontal line) over text.

/web/html/element/strong.name: strong
/web/html/element/strong.summary: The `<strong>` HTML element indicates that its contents have strong importance, seriousness, or urgency. Browsers typically render the contents in bold type.

/web/html/element/style.name: style
/web/html/element/style.summary: The `<style>` HTML element contains style information for a document, or part of a document. It contains CSS, which is applied to the contents of the document containing the `<style>` element.

/web/html/element/style/attributes/media.name: media
/web/html/element/style/attributes/media.summary: This attribute defines which media the style should be applied to. Its value is a media query, which defaults to `all` if the attribute is missing.

/web/html/element/style/attributes/nonce.name: nonce
/web/html/element/style/attributes/nonce.summary: A cryptographic nonce (number used once) used to allow inline styles in a style-src Content-Security-Policy. The server must generate a unique nonce value each time it transmits a policy. It is critical to provide a nonce that cannot be guessed as bypassing a resource's policy is otherwise trivial.

/web/html/element/style/attributes/title.name: title
/web/html/element/style/attributes/title.summary: This attribute specifies alternative style sheet sets.

/web/html/element/sub.name: sub
/web/html/element/sub.summary: The `<sub>` HTML element specifies inline text which should be displayed as subscript for solely typographical reasons. Subscripts are typically rendered with a lowered baseline using smaller text.

/web/html/element/summary.name: summary
/web/html/element/summary.summary: The `<summary>` HTML element specifies a summary, caption, or legend for a details element's disclosure box. Clicking the `<summary>` element toggles the state of the parent `<details>` element open and closed.

/web/html/element/sup.name: sup
/web/html/element/sup.summary: The `<sup>` HTML element specifies inline text which is to be displayed as superscript for solely typographical reasons. Superscripts are usually rendered with a raised baseline using smaller text.

/web/html/element/table.name: table
/web/html/element/table.summary: The `<table>` HTML element represents tabular data  that is, information presented in a two-dimensional table comprised of rows and columns of cells containing data.

/web/html/element/tbody.name: tbody
/web/html/element/tbody.summary: The `<tbody>` HTML element encapsulates a set of table rows (tr elements), indicating that they comprise the body of the table (table).

/web/html/element/td.name: td
/web/html/element/td.summary: The `<td>` HTML element defines a cell of a table that contains data. It participates in the table model.

/web/html/element/td/attributes/colspan.name: colspan
/web/html/element/td/attributes/colspan.summary: This attribute contains a non-negative integer value that indicates for how many columns the cell extends. Its default value is `1`. Values higher than 1000 will be considered as incorrect and will be set to the default value (1).

/web/html/element/td/attributes/headers.name: headers
/web/html/element/td/attributes/headers.summary: This attribute contains a list of space-separated strings, each corresponding to the id attribute of the th elements that apply to this element.

/web/html/element/td/attributes/rowspan.name: rowspan
/web/html/element/td/attributes/rowspan.summary: This attribute contains a non-negative integer value that indicates for how many rows the cell extends. Its default value is `1`; if its value is set to `0`, it extends until the end of the table section (thead, tbody, tfoot, even if implicitly defined), that the cell belongs to. Values higher than 65534 are clipped down to 65534.

/web/html/element/template.name: template
/web/html/element/template.summary: The `<template>` HTML element is a mechanism for holding HTML that is not to be rendered immediately when a page is loaded but may be instantiated subsequently during runtime using JavaScript.

/web/html/element/textarea.name: textarea
/web/html/element/textarea.summary: The `<textarea>` HTML element represents a multi-line plain-text editing control, useful when you want to allow users to enter a sizeable amount of free-form text, for example a comment on a review or feedback form.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/au.name: autocomplete
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/au.summary: This attribute indicates whether the value of the control can be automatically completed by the browser. Possible values are.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/au.name: autocorrect
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/au.summary: A string which indicates whether or not to activate automatic spelling correction and processing of text substitutions (if any are configured) while the user is editing this `textarea`. Permitted values are.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/au.name: autofocus
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/au.summary: This Boolean attribute lets you specify that a form control should have input focus when the page loads. Only one form-associated element in a document can have this attribute specified.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/co.name: cols
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/co.summary: The visible width of the text control, in average character widths. If it is specified, it must be a positive integer. If it is not specified, the default value is `20`.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/di.name: disabled
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/di.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates that the user cannot interact with the control. If this attribute is not specified, the control inherits its setting from the containing element, for example fieldset; if there is no containing element when the `disabled` attribute is set, the control is enabled.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/fo.name: form
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/fo.summary: The form element that the `<textarea>` element is associated with (its "form owner"). The value of the attribute must be the `id` of a form element in the same document. If this attribute is not specified, the `<textarea>` element must be a descendant of a form element. This attribute enables you to place `<textarea>` elements anywhere within a document, not just as descendants of form elements.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/ma.name: maxlength
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/ma.summary: The maximum number of characters (UTF-16 code units) that the user can enter. If this value isn't specified, the user can enter an unlimited number of characters.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/mi.name: minlength
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/mi.summary: The minimum number of characters (UTF-16 code units) required that the user should enter.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/pl.name: placeholder
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/pl.summary: A hint to the user of what can be entered in the control. Carriage returns or line-feeds within the placeholder text must be treated as line breaks when rendering the hint.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/re.name: readonly
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/re.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates that the user cannot modify the value of the control. Unlike the `disabled` attribute, the `readonly` attribute does not prevent the user from clicking or selecting in the control. The value of a read-only control is still submitted with the form.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/re.name: required
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/re.summary: This attribute specifies that the user must fill in a value before submitting a form.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/ro.name: rows
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/ro.summary: The number of visible text lines for the control. If it is specified, it must be a positive integer. If it is not specified, the default value is 2.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/sp.name: spellcheck
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/sp.summary: Specifies whether the `<textarea>` is subject to spell checking by the underlying browser/OS. The value can be.

/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/wr.name: wrap
/web/html/element/textarea/attributes/wr.summary: Indicates how the control wraps text. Possible values are.

/web/html/element/tfoot.name: tfoot
/web/html/element/tfoot.summary: The `<tfoot>` HTML element defines a set of rows summarizing the columns of the table.

/web/html/element/th.name: th
/web/html/element/th.summary: The `<th>` HTML element defines a cell as header of a group of table cells. The exact nature of this group is defined by the scope and headers attributes.

/web/html/element/th/attributes/abbr.name: abbr
/web/html/element/th/attributes/abbr.summary: This attribute contains a short abbreviated description of the cell's content. Some user-agents, such as speech readers, may present this description before the content itself.

/web/html/element/th/attributes/colspan.name: colspan
/web/html/element/th/attributes/colspan.summary: This attribute contains a non-negative integer value that indicates for how many columns the cell extends. Its default value is `1`. Values higher than 1000 will be considered as incorrect and will be set to the default value (1).

/web/html/element/th/attributes/headers.name: headers
/web/html/element/th/attributes/headers.summary: This attribute contains a list of space-separated strings, each corresponding to the id attribute of the th elements that apply to this element.

/web/html/element/th/attributes/rowspan.name: rowspan
/web/html/element/th/attributes/rowspan.summary: This attribute contains a non-negative integer value that indicates for how many rows the cell extends. Its default value is `1`; if its value is set to `0`, it extends until the end of the table section (thead, tbody, tfoot, even if implicitly defined), that the cell belongs to. Values higher than 65534 are clipped down to 65534.

/web/html/element/th/attributes/scope.name: scope
/web/html/element/th/attributes/scope.summary: This enumerated attribute defines the cells that the header (defined in the th) element relates to. It may have the following values.

/web/html/element/thead.name: thead
/web/html/element/thead.summary: The `<thead>` HTML element defines a set of rows defining the head of the columns of the table.

/web/html/element/time.name: time
/web/html/element/time.summary: The `<time>` HTML element represents a specific period in time. It may include the `datetime` attribute to translate dates into machine-readable format, allowing for better search engine results or custom features such as reminders.

/web/html/element/time/attributes/dateti.name: datetime
/web/html/element/time/attributes/dateti.summary: This attribute indicates the time and/or date of the element and must be in one of the formats described below.

/web/html/element/title.name: title
/web/html/element/title.summary: The `<title>` HTML element defines the document's title that is shown in a Browser's title bar or a page's tab. It only contains text; tags within the element are ignored.

/web/html/element/tr.name: tr
/web/html/element/tr.summary: The `<tr>` HTML element defines a row of cells in a table. The row's cells can then be established using a mix of td (data cell) and th (header cell) elements.

/web/html/element/track.name: track
/web/html/element/track.summary: The `<track>` HTML element is used as a child of the media elements, audio and video. It lets you specify timed text tracks (or time-based data), for example to automatically handle subtitles. The tracks are formatted in WebVTT format (`.vtt` files)  Web Video Text Tracks.

/web/html/element/track/attributes/defau.name: default
/web/html/element/track/attributes/defau.summary: This attribute indicates that the track should be enabled unless the user's preferences indicate that another track is more appropriate. This may only be used on one `track` element per media element.

/web/html/element/track/attributes/kind.name: kind
/web/html/element/track/attributes/kind.summary: How the text track is meant to be used. If omitted the default kind is `subtitles`. If the attribute contains an invalid value, it will use `metadata` (Versions of Chrome earlier than 52 treated an invalid value as `subtitles`). The following keywords are allowed.

/web/html/element/track/attributes/label.name: label
/web/html/element/track/attributes/label.summary: A user-readable title of the text track which is used by the browser when listing available text tracks.

/web/html/element/track/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/track/attributes/src.summary: Address of the track (`.vtt` file). Must be a valid URL. This attribute must be specified and its URL value must have the same origin as the document  unless the audio or video parent element of the `track` element has a `crossorigin` attribute.

/web/html/element/track/attributes/srcla.name: srclang
/web/html/element/track/attributes/srcla.summary: Language of the track text data. It must be a valid BCP 47 language tag. If the `kind` attribute is set to `subtitles`, then `srclang` must be defined.

/web/html/element/tt.name: tt
/web/html/element/tt.summary: The `<tt>` HTML element creates inline text which is presented using the user agent default monospace font face. This element was created for the purpose of rendering text as it would be displayed on a fixed-width display such as a teletype, text-only screen, or line printer.

/web/html/element/u.name: u
/web/html/element/u.summary: The `<u>` HTML element represents a span of inline text which should be rendered in a way that indicates that it has a non-textual annotation. This is rendered by default as a simple solid underline, but may be altered using CSS.

/web/html/element/ul.name: ul
/web/html/element/ul.summary: The `<ul>` HTML element represents an unordered list of items, typically rendered as a bulleted list.

/web/html/element/ul/attributes/compact.name: compact
/web/html/element/ul/attributes/compact.summary: This Boolean attribute hints that the list should be rendered in a compact style. The interpretation of this attribute depends on the user agent, and it doesn't work in all browsers.

/web/html/element/ul/attributes/type.name: type
/web/html/element/ul/attributes/type.summary: This attribute sets the bullet style for the list. The values defined under HTML3.2 and the transitional version of HTML 4.0/4.01 are.

/web/html/element/var.name: var
/web/html/element/var.summary: The `<var>` HTML element represents the name of a variable in a mathematical expression or a programming context. It's typically presented using an italicized version of the current typeface, although that behavior is browser-dependent.

/web/html/element/video.name: video
/web/html/element/video.summary: The `<video>` HTML element embeds a media player which supports video playback into the document. You can use `<video>` for audio content as well, but the audio element may provide a more appropriate user experience.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/autop.name: autoplay
/web/html/element/video/attributes/autop.summary: A Boolean attribute; if specified, the video automatically begins to play back as soon as it can do so without stopping to finish loading the data.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/autop.name: autopictureinpicture
/web/html/element/video/attributes/autop.summary: A Boolean attribute which if `true` indicates that the element should automatically toggle picture-in-picture mode when the user switches back and forth between this document and another document or application.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/contr.name: controls
/web/html/element/video/attributes/contr.summary: If this attribute is present, the browser will offer controls to allow the user to control video playback, including volume, seeking, and pause/resume playback.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/contr.name: controlslist
/web/html/element/video/attributes/contr.summary: The `controlslist` attribute, when specified, helps the browser select what controls to show on the media element whenever the browser shows its own set of controls (e.g. when the `controls` attribute is specified).

/web/html/element/video/attributes/cross.name: crossorigin
/web/html/element/video/attributes/cross.summary: This enumerated attribute indicates whether to use CORS to fetch the related video. CORS-enabled resources can be reused in the canvas element without being tainted. The allowed values are.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/disab.name: disablepictureinpicture
/web/html/element/video/attributes/disab.summary: Prevents the browser from suggesting a Picture-in-Picture context menu or to request Picture-in-Picture automatically in some cases.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/disab.name: disableremoteplayback
/web/html/element/video/attributes/disab.summary: A Boolean attribute used to disable the capability of remote playback in devices that are attached using wired (HDMI, DVI, etc.) and wireless technologies (Miracast, Chromecast, DLNA, AirPlay, etc).

/web/html/element/video/attributes/heigh.name: height
/web/html/element/video/attributes/heigh.summary: The height of the video's display area, in CSS pixels (absolute values only; no percentages.)

/web/html/element/video/attributes/loop.name: loop
/web/html/element/video/attributes/loop.summary: A Boolean attribute; if specified, the browser will automatically seek back to the start upon reaching the end of the video.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/muted.name: muted
/web/html/element/video/attributes/muted.summary: A Boolean attribute that indicates the default setting of the audio contained in the video. If set, the audio will be initially silenced. Its default value is `false`, meaning that the audio will be played when the video is played.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/plays.name: playsinline
/web/html/element/video/attributes/plays.summary: A Boolean attribute indicating that the video is to be played "inline", that is within the element's playback area. Note that the absence of this attribute does not imply that the video will always be played in fullscreen.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/poste.name: poster
/web/html/element/video/attributes/poste.summary: A URL for an image to be shown while the video is downloading. If this attribute isn't specified, nothing is displayed until the first frame is available, then the first frame is shown as the poster frame.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/prelo.name: preload
/web/html/element/video/attributes/prelo.summary: This enumerated attribute is intended to provide a hint to the browser about what the author thinks will lead to the best user experience with regards to what content is loaded before the video is played. It may have one of the following values.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/src.name: src
/web/html/element/video/attributes/src.summary: The URL of the video to embed. This is optional; you may instead use the source element within the video block to specify the video to embed.

/web/html/element/video/attributes/width.name: width
/web/html/element/video/attributes/width.summary: The width of the video's display area, in CSS pixels (absolute values only; no percentages).

/web/html/element/wbr.name: wbr
/web/html/element/wbr.summary: The `<wbr>` HTML element represents a word break opportunitya position within text where the browser may optionally break a line, though its line-breaking rules would not otherwise create a break at that location.

/web/html/element/xmp.name: xmp
/web/html/element/xmp.summary: The `<xmp>` HTML element renders text between the start and end tags without interpreting the HTML in between and using a monospaced font. The HTML2 specification recommended that it should be rendered wide enough to allow 80 characters per line.

/web/svg/element/a.name: a
/web/svg/element/a.summary: The <a> SVG element creates a hyperlink to other web pages, files, locations in the same page, email addresses, or any other URL. It is very similar to HTML's a element.

/web/svg/element/a/attributes/href.name: href
/web/svg/element/a/attributes/href.summary: The URL or URL fragment the hyperlink points to.

/web/svg/element/a/attributes/target.name: target
/web/svg/element/a/attributes/target.summary: Where to display the linked URL.

/web/svg/element/a/attributes/xlink:href.name: xlink:href
/web/svg/element/a/attributes/xlink:href.summary: The URL or URL fragment that the hyperlink points to. May be required for backwards compatibility for older browsers.

/web/svg/element/altglyph.name: altGlyph
/web/svg/element/altglyph.summary: The `<altGlyph>` SVG element allows sophisticated selection of the glyphs used to render its child character data.

/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/x.name: x
/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/x.summary: This attribute defines the corresponding absolute x-coordinates for rendering the element.

/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/y.name: y
/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/y.summary: This attribute defines the corresponding absolute y-coordinates for rendering the element.

/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/dx.name: dx
/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/dx.summary: This attribute indicates a shift along the x-axis on the position of the element.

/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/dy.name: dy
/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/dy.summary: This attribute indicates a shift along the x-axis on the position of the element.

/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/rot.name: rotate
/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/rot.summary: This attribute defines the supplemental rotation that will be applied to the element.

/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/gly.name: glyphRef
/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/gly.summary: The glyph identifier, the format of which is dependent on the format defined by the `format` attribute of the given font.

/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/for.name: format
/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/for.summary: The format of the given font.

/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/xli.name: xlink:href
/web/svg/element/altglyph/attributes/xli.summary: An <iri> reference either to a glyph element in an SVG document or to an altGlyphDef element.

/web/svg/element/altglyphdef.name: altGlyphDef
/web/svg/element/altglyphdef.summary: The `<altGlyphDef>` SVG element defines a substitution representation for glyphs.

/web/svg/element/altglyphitem.name: altGlyphItem
/web/svg/element/altglyphitem.summary: The `<altGlyphItem>` element provides a set of candidates for glyph substitution by the altGlyph element.

/web/svg/element/animate.name: animate
/web/svg/element/animate.summary: The SVG `<animate>` element provides a way to animate an attribute of an element over time.

/web/svg/element/animatemotion.name: animateMotion
/web/svg/element/animatemotion.summary: The SVG `<animateMotion>` element provides a way to define how an element moves along a motion path.

/web/svg/element/animatemotion/attribute.name: keyPoints
/web/svg/element/animatemotion/attribute.summary: This attribute indicate, in the range [0,1], how far is the object along the path for each keyTimes associated values.

/web/svg/element/animatemotion/attribute.name: path
/web/svg/element/animatemotion/attribute.summary: This attribute defines the path of the motion, using the same syntax as the  attribute.

/web/svg/element/animatemotion/attribute.name: rotate
/web/svg/element/animatemotion/attribute.summary: This attribute defines a rotation applied to the element animated along a path, usually to make it pointing in the direction of the animation.

/web/svg/element/animatetransform.name: animateTransform
/web/svg/element/animatetransform.summary: The `animateTransform` element animates a transformation attribute on its target element, thereby allowing animations to control translation, scaling, rotation, and/or skewing.

/web/svg/element/circle.name: circle
/web/svg/element/circle.summary: The `<circle>` SVG element is an SVG basic shape, used to draw circles based on a center point and a radius.

/web/svg/element/circle/attributes/cx.name: cx
/web/svg/element/circle/attributes/cx.summary: The x-axis coordinate of the center of the circle.

/web/svg/element/circle/attributes/cy.name: cy
/web/svg/element/circle/attributes/cy.summary: The y-axis coordinate of the center of the circle.

/web/svg/element/circle/attributes/r.name: r
/web/svg/element/circle/attributes/r.summary: The radius of the circle. A value lower or equal to zero disables rendering of the circle.

/web/svg/element/circle/attributes/pathL.name: pathLength
/web/svg/element/circle/attributes/pathL.summary: The total length for the circle's circumference, in user units.

/web/svg/element/clippath.name: clipPath
/web/svg/element/clippath.summary: The `<clipPath>` SVG element defines a clipping path, to be used by the clip-path property.

/web/svg/element/clippath/attributes/cli.name: clipPathUnits
/web/svg/element/clippath/attributes/cli.summary: Defines the coordinate system for the contents of the `<clipPath>` element.

/web/svg/element/cursor.name: cursor
/web/svg/element/cursor.summary: Note: The CSS cursor property should be used instead of this element.

/web/svg/element/defs.name: defs
/web/svg/element/defs.summary: The `<defs>` element is used to store graphical objects that will be used at a later time. Objects created inside a `<defs>` element are not rendered directly. To display them you have to reference them (with a use element for example).

/web/svg/element/desc.name: desc
/web/svg/element/desc.summary: The `<desc>` element provides an accessible, long-text description of any SVG container element or graphics element.

/web/svg/element/discard.name: discard
/web/svg/element/discard.summary: The `<discard>` SVG element allows authors to specify the time at which particular elements are to be discarded, thereby reducing the resources required by an SVG user agent. This is particularly useful to help SVG viewers conserve memory while displaying long-running documents.

/web/svg/element/ellipse.name: ellipse
/web/svg/element/ellipse.summary: The `<ellipse>` element is an SVG basic shape, used to create ellipses based on a center coordinate, and both their x and y radius.

/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/cx.name: cx
/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/cx.summary: The x position of the ellipse.

/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/cy.name: cy
/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/cy.summary: The y position of the ellipse.

/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/rx.name: rx
/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/rx.summary: The radius of the ellipse on the x axis.

/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/ry.name: ry
/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/ry.summary: The radius of the ellipse on the y axis.

/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/path.name: pathLength
/web/svg/element/ellipse/attributes/path.summary: This attribute lets specify the total length for the path, in user units.

/web/svg/element/feblend.name: feBlend
/web/svg/element/feblend.summary: The `<feBlend>` SVG filter primitive composes two objects together ruled by a certain blending mode. This is similar to what is known from image editing software when blending two layers. The mode is defined by the mode attribute.

/web/svg/element/fecolormatrix.name: feColorMatrix
/web/svg/element/fecolormatrix.summary: The `<feColorMatrix>` SVG filter element changes colors based on a transformation matrix. Every pixel's color value `[R,G,B,A]` is matrix multiplied by a 5 by 5 color matrix to create new color `[R',G',B',A']`.

/web/svg/element/fecomponenttransfer.name: feComponentTransfer
/web/svg/element/fecomponenttransfer.summary: The `<feComponentTransfer>` SVG filter primitive performs color-component-wise remapping of data for each pixel. It allows operations like brightness adjustment, contrast adjustment, color balance or thresholding.

/web/svg/element/fecomposite.name: feComposite
/web/svg/element/fecomposite.summary: The `<feComposite>` SVG filter primitive performs the combination of two input images pixel-wise in image space using one of the Porter-Duff compositing operations: `over`, `in`, `atop`, `out`, `xor`, `lighter`, or `arithmetic`.

/web/svg/element/feconvolvematrix.name: feConvolveMatrix
/web/svg/element/feconvolvematrix.summary: The `<feConvolveMatrix>` SVG filter primitive applies a matrix convolution filter effect. A convolution combines pixels in the input image with neighboring pixels to produce a resulting image. A wide variety of imaging operations can be achieved through convolutions, including blurring, edge detection, sharpening, embossing and beveling.

/web/svg/element/fediffuselighting.name: feDiffuseLighting
/web/svg/element/fediffuselighting.summary: The `<feDiffuseLighting>` SVG filter primitive lights an image using the alpha channel as a bump map. The resulting image, which is an RGBA opaque image, depends on the light color, light position and surface geometry of the input bump map.

/web/svg/element/fedisplacementmap.name: feDisplacementMap
/web/svg/element/fedisplacementmap.summary: The `<feDisplacementMap>` SVG filter primitive uses the pixel values from the image from in2 to spatially displace the image from in.

/web/svg/element/fedistantlight.name: feDistantLight
/web/svg/element/fedistantlight.summary: The `<feDistantLight>` filter primitive defines a distant light source that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: feDiffuseLighting or feSpecularLighting.

/web/svg/element/fedropshadow.name: feDropShadow
/web/svg/element/fedropshadow.summary: The SVG `<feDropShadow>` filter primitive creates a drop shadow of the input image. It can only be used inside a  element.

/web/svg/element/fedropshadow/attributes.name: dx
/web/svg/element/fedropshadow/attributes.summary: This attribute defines the x offset of the drop shadow.

/web/svg/element/fedropshadow/attributes.name: dy
/web/svg/element/fedropshadow/attributes.summary: This attribute defines the y offset of the drop shadow.

/web/svg/element/fedropshadow/attributes.name: stdDeviation
/web/svg/element/fedropshadow/attributes.summary: This attribute defines the standard deviation for the blur operation in the drop shadow.

/web/svg/element/feflood.name: feFlood
/web/svg/element/feflood.summary: The `<feFlood>` SVG filter primitive fills the filter subregion with the color and opacity defined by flood-color and flood-opacity.

/web/svg/element/fefunca.name: feFuncA
/web/svg/element/fefunca.summary: The `<feFuncA>` SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the alpha component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.

/web/svg/element/fefuncb.name: feFuncB
/web/svg/element/fefuncb.summary: The `<feFuncB>` SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the blue component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.

/web/svg/element/fefuncg.name: feFuncG
/web/svg/element/fefuncg.summary: The `<feFuncG>` SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the green component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.

/web/svg/element/fefuncr.name: feFuncR
/web/svg/element/fefuncr.summary: The `<feFuncR>` SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the red component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.

/web/svg/element/fegaussianblur.name: feGaussianBlur
