/web/svg/element/fegaussianblur.summary: The `<feGaussianBlur>` SVG filter primitive blurs the input image by the amount specified in stdDeviation, which defines the bell-curve.

/web/svg/element/feimage.name: feImage
/web/svg/element/feimage.summary: The `<feImage>` SVG filter primitive fetches image data from an external source and provides the pixel data as output (meaning if the external source is an SVG image, it is rasterized.)

/web/svg/element/femerge.name: feMerge
/web/svg/element/femerge.summary: The `<feMerge>` SVG element allows filter effects to be applied concurrently instead of sequentially. This is achieved by other filters storing their output via the result attribute and then accessing it in a feMergeNode child.

/web/svg/element/femergenode.name: feMergeNode
/web/svg/element/femergenode.summary: The `feMergeNode` takes the result of another filter to be processed by its parent feMerge.

/web/svg/element/femorphology.name: feMorphology
/web/svg/element/femorphology.summary: The `<feMorphology>` SVG filter primitive is used to erode or dilate the input image. Its usefulness lies especially in fattening or thinning effects.

/web/svg/element/feoffset.name: feOffset
/web/svg/element/feoffset.summary: The `<feOffset>` SVG filter primitive allows to offset the input image. The input image as a whole is offset by the values specified in the dx and dy attributes.

/web/svg/element/fepointlight.name: fePointLight
/web/svg/element/fepointlight.summary: The `<fePointLight>` filter primitive defines a light source which allows to create a point light effect. It that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: feDiffuseLighting or feSpecularLighting.

/web/svg/element/fespecularlighting.name: feSpecularLighting
/web/svg/element/fespecularlighting.summary: The `<feSpecularLighting>` SVG filter primitive lights a source graphic using the alpha channel as a bump map. The resulting image is an RGBA image based on the light color. The lighting calculation follows the standard specular component of the Phong lighting model. The resulting image depends on the light color, light position and surface geometry of the input bump map. The result of the lighting calculation is added. The filter primitive assumes that the viewer is at infinity in the z direction.

/web/svg/element/fespotlight.name: feSpotLight
/web/svg/element/fespotlight.summary: The `<feSpotLight>` SVG filter primitive defines a light source that can be used to create a spotlight effect. It is used within a lighting filter primitive: feDiffuseLighting or feSpecularLighting.

/web/svg/element/fetile.name: feTile
/web/svg/element/fetile.summary: The `<feTile>` SVG filter primitive allows to fill a target rectangle with a repeated, tiled pattern of an input image. The effect is similar to the one of a pattern.

/web/svg/element/feturbulence.name: feTurbulence
/web/svg/element/feturbulence.summary: The `<feTurbulence>` SVG filter primitive creates an image using the Perlin turbulence function. It allows the synthesis of artificial textures like clouds or marble. The resulting image will fill the entire filter primitive subregion.

/web/svg/element/filter.name: filter
/web/svg/element/filter.summary: The `<filter>` SVG element defines a custom filter effect by grouping atomic filter primitives. It is never rendered itself, but must be used by the filter attribute on SVG elements, or the filter CSS property for SVG/HTML elements.

/web/svg/element/font.name: font
/web/svg/element/font.summary: The `<font>` SVG element defines a font to be used for text layout.

/web/svg/element/font-face.name: font-face
/web/svg/element/font-face.summary: The `<font-face>` SVG element corresponds to the CSS @font-face rule. It defines a font's outer properties.

/web/svg/element/font-face-format.name: font-face-format
/web/svg/element/font-face-format.summary: The `<font-face-format>` SVG element describes the type of font referenced by its parent font-face-uri.

/web/svg/element/font-face-name.name: font-face-name
/web/svg/element/font-face-name.summary: The `<font-face-name>` element points to a locally installed copy of this font, identified by its name.

/web/svg/element/font-face-src.name: font-face-src
/web/svg/element/font-face-src.summary: The `<font-face-src>` SVG element corresponds to the @font-face/src descriptor in CSS @font-face rules. It serves as container for font-face-name, pointing to locally installed copies of this font, and font-face-uri, utilizing remotely defined fonts.

/web/svg/element/font-face-uri.name: font-face-uri
/web/svg/element/font-face-uri.summary: The `<font-face-uri>` SVG element points to a remote definition of the current font.

/web/svg/element/foreignobject.name: foreignObject
/web/svg/element/foreignobject.summary: The `<foreignObject>` SVG element includes elements from a different XML namespace. In the context of a browser, it is most likely (X)HTML.

/web/svg/element/foreignobject/attribute.name: x
/web/svg/element/foreignobject/attribute.summary: The x coordinate of the foreignObject.

/web/svg/element/foreignobject/attribute.name: y
/web/svg/element/foreignobject/attribute.summary: The y coordinate of the foreignObject.

/web/svg/element/g.name: g
/web/svg/element/g.summary: The `<g>` SVG element is a container used to group other SVG elements.

/web/svg/element/glyph.name: glyph
/web/svg/element/glyph.summary: A `<glyph>` defines a single glyph in an SVG font.

/web/svg/element/glyphref.name: glyphRef
/web/svg/element/glyphref.summary: The `glyphRef` element provides a single possible glyph to the referencing altGlyph substitution.

/web/svg/element/hkern.name: hkern
/web/svg/element/hkern.summary: The `<hkern>` SVG element allows to fine-tweak the horizontal distance between two glyphs. This process is known as kerning.

/web/svg/element/image.name: image
/web/svg/element/image.summary: The `<image>` SVG element includes images inside SVG documents. It can display raster image files or other SVG files.

/web/svg/element/line.name: line
/web/svg/element/line.summary: The `<line>` element is an SVG basic shape used to create a line connecting two points.

/web/svg/element/line/attributes/x1.name: x1
/web/svg/element/line/attributes/x1.summary: Defines the x-axis coordinate of the line starting point.

/web/svg/element/line/attributes/x2.name: x2
/web/svg/element/line/attributes/x2.summary: Defines the x-axis coordinate of the line ending point.

/web/svg/element/line/attributes/y1.name: y1
/web/svg/element/line/attributes/y1.summary: Defines the y-axis coordinate of the line starting point.

/web/svg/element/line/attributes/y2.name: y2
/web/svg/element/line/attributes/y2.summary: Defines the y-axis coordinate of the line ending point.

/web/svg/element/line/attributes/pathLen.name: pathLength
/web/svg/element/line/attributes/pathLen.summary: Defines the total path length in user units.

/web/svg/element/lineargradient.name: linearGradient
/web/svg/element/lineargradient.summary: The `<linearGradient>` element lets authors define linear gradients to apply to other SVG elements.

/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.name: gradientUnits
/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the coordinate system for attributes `x1`, `x2`, `y1`, `y2`

/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.name: gradientTransform
/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.summary: This attribute provides additional transformation to the gradient coordinate system.

/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.name: href
/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines a reference to another `<linearGradient>` element that will be used as a template.

/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.name: spreadMethod
/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.summary: This attribute indicates how the gradient behaves if it starts or ends inside the bounds of the shape containing the gradient.

/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.name: x1
/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the x coordinate of the starting point of the vector gradient along which the linear gradient is drawn.

/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.name: x2
/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the x coordinate of the ending point of the vector gradient along which the linear gradient is drawn.

/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.name: xlink:href
/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.summary: An <IRI> reference to another `<linearGradient>` element that will be used as a template.

/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.name: y1
/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the y coordinate of the starting point of the vector gradient along which the linear gradient is drawn.

/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.name: y2
/web/svg/element/lineargradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the y coordinate of the ending point of the vector gradient along which the linear gradient is drawn.

/web/svg/element/marker.name: marker
/web/svg/element/marker.summary: The `<marker>` element defines the graphic that is to be used for drawing arrowheads or polymarkers on a given path, line, polyline or polygon element.

/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/marke.name: markerHeight
/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/marke.summary: This attribute defines the height of the marker viewport.

/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/marke.name: markerUnits
/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/marke.summary: This attribute defines the coordinate system for the attributes `markerWidth`, `markerHeight` and the contents of the `<marker>`.

/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/marke.name: markerWidth
/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/marke.summary: This attribute defines the width of the marker viewport.

/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/orien.name: orient
/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/orien.summary: This attribute defines the orientation of the marker relative to the shape it is attached to.

/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/prese.name: preserveAspectRatio
/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/prese.summary: This attribute defines how the svg fragment must be deformed if it is embedded in a container with a different aspect ratio.

/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/refX.name: refX
/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/refX.summary: This attribute defines the x coordinate for the reference point of the marker.

/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/refY.name: refY
/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/refY.summary: This attribute defines the y coordinate for the reference point of the marker.

/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/viewB.name: viewBox
/web/svg/element/marker/attributes/viewB.summary: This attribute defines the bound of the SVG viewport for the current SVG fragment.

/web/svg/element/mask.name: mask
/web/svg/element/mask.summary: The `<mask>` element defines an alpha mask for compositing the current object into the background. A mask is used/referenced using the mask property.

/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/height.name: height
/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/height.summary: This attribute defines the height of the masking area.

/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/maskCon.name: maskContentUnits
/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/maskCon.summary: This attribute defines the coordinate system for the contents of the `<mask>`.

/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/maskUni.name: maskUnits
/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/maskUni.summary: This attribute defines the coordinate system for attributes x, y, width and height on the `<mask>`.

/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/x.name: x
/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/x.summary: This attribute defines the x-axis coordinate of the top-left corner of the masking area.

/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/y.name: y
/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/y.summary: This attribute defines the y-axis coordinate of the top-left corner of the masking area.

/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/width.name: width
/web/svg/element/mask/attributes/width.summary: This attribute defines the width of the masking area.

/web/svg/element/metadata.name: metadata
/web/svg/element/metadata.summary: The `<metadata>` SVG element adds metadata to SVG content. Metadata is structured information about data. The contents of `<metadata>` should be elements from other XML namespace such as RDF, FOAF, etc.

/web/svg/element/missing-glyph.name: missing-glyph
/web/svg/element/missing-glyph.summary: The `<missing-glyph>` SVG element's content is rendered, if for a given character the font doesn't define an appropriate glyph.

/web/svg/element/mpath.name: mpath
/web/svg/element/mpath.summary: The `<mpath>` sub-element for the animateMotion element provides the ability to reference an external path element as the definition of a motion path.

/web/svg/element/path.name: path
/web/svg/element/path.summary: The `<path>` SVG element is the generic element to define a shape. All the basic shapes can be created with a path element.

/web/svg/element/path/attributes/d.name: d
/web/svg/element/path/attributes/d.summary: This attribute defines the shape of the path.

/web/svg/element/path/attributes/pathLen.name: pathLength
/web/svg/element/path/attributes/pathLen.summary: This attribute lets authors specify the total length for the path, in user units.

/web/svg/element/pattern.name: pattern
/web/svg/element/pattern.summary: The `<pattern>` element defines a graphics object which can be redrawn at repeated x- and y-coordinate intervals ("tiled") to cover an area.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/heig.name: height
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/heig.summary: This attribute determines the height of the pattern tile.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/href.name: href
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/href.summary: This attribute reference a template pattern that provides default values for the `<pattern>` attributes.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/patt.name: patternContentUnits
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/patt.summary: This attribute defines the coordinate system for the contents of the pattern.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/patt.name: patternTransform
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/patt.summary: This attribute contains the definition of an optional additional transformation from the pattern coordinate system onto the target coordinate system.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/patt.name: patternUnits
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/patt.summary: This attribute defines the coordinate system for attributes `x`, `y`, `width` , and `height`.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/pres.name: preserveAspectRatio
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/pres.summary: This attribute defines how the SVG fragment must be deformed if it is embedded in a container with a different aspect ratio.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/view.name: viewBox
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/view.summary: This attribute defines the bound of the SVG viewport for the pattern fragment.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/widt.name: width
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/widt.summary: This attribute determines the width of the pattern tile.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/x.name: x
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/x.summary: This attribute determines the x coordinate shift of the pattern tile.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/xlin.name: xlink:href
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/xlin.summary: This attribute reference a template pattern that provides default values for the `<pattern>` attributes.

/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/y.name: y
/web/svg/element/pattern/attributes/y.summary: This attribute determines the y coordinate shift of the pattern tile.

/web/svg/element/polygon.name: polygon
/web/svg/element/polygon.summary: The `<polygon>` element defines a closed shape consisting of a set of connected straight line segments. The last point is connected to the first point.

/web/svg/element/polygon/attributes/poin.name: points
/web/svg/element/polygon/attributes/poin.summary: This attribute defines the list of points (pairs of `x,y` absolute coordinates) required to draw the polygon.

/web/svg/element/polygon/attributes/path.name: pathLength
/web/svg/element/polygon/attributes/path.summary: This attribute lets specify the total length for the path, in user units.

/web/svg/element/polyline.name: polyline
/web/svg/element/polyline.summary: The `<polyline>` SVG element is an SVG basic shape that creates straight lines connecting several points. Typically a `polyline` is used to create open shapes as the last point doesn't have to be connected to the first point. For closed shapes see the polygon element.

/web/svg/element/polyline/attributes/poi.name: points
/web/svg/element/polyline/attributes/poi.summary: This attribute defines the list of points (pairs of x,y absolute coordinates) required to draw the polyline

/web/svg/element/polyline/attributes/pat.name: pathLength
/web/svg/element/polyline/attributes/pat.summary: This attribute lets specify the total length for the path, in user units.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient.name: radialGradient
/web/svg/element/radialgradient.summary: The `<radialGradient>` element lets authors define radial gradients that can be applied to fill or stroke of graphical elements.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: cx
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the x coordinate of the end circle of the radial gradient.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: cy
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the y coordinate of the end circle of the radial gradient.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: fr
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the radius of the start circle of the radial gradient. The gradient will be drawn such that the 0%  is mapped to the perimeter of the start circle.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: fx
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the x coordinate of the start circle of the radial gradient.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: fy
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the y coordinate of the start circle of the radial gradient.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: gradientUnits
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the coordinate system for attributes `cx`, `cy`, `r`, `fx`, `fy`, `fr`

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: gradientTransform
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute provides additional transformation to the gradient coordinate system.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: href
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines a reference to another `<radialGradient>` element that will be used as a template.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: r
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute defines the radius of the end circle of the radial gradient. The gradient will be drawn such that the 100%  is mapped to the perimeter of the end circle.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: spreadMethod
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: This attribute indicates how the gradient behaves if it starts or ends inside the bounds of the shape containing the gradient.

/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.name: xlink:href
/web/svg/element/radialgradient/attribut.summary: An <IRI> reference to another `<radialGradient>` element that will be used as a template.

/web/svg/element/rect.name: rect
/web/svg/element/rect.summary: The `<rect>` element is a basic SVG shape that draws rectangles, defined by their position, width, and height. The rectangles may have their corners rounded.

/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/x.name: x
/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/x.summary: The x coordinate of the rect.

/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/y.name: y
/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/y.summary: The y coordinate of the rect.

/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/rx.name: rx
/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/rx.summary: The horizontal corner radius of the rect. Defaults to `ry` if it is specified.

/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/ry.name: ry
/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/ry.summary: The vertical corner radius of the rect. Defaults to `rx` if it is specified.

/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/pathLen.name: pathLength
/web/svg/element/rect/attributes/pathLen.summary: The total length of the rectangle's perimeter, in user units.

/web/svg/element/script.name: script
/web/svg/element/script.summary: The SVG `script` element allows to add scripts to an SVG document.

/web/svg/element/script/attributes/href.name: href
/web/svg/element/script/attributes/href.summary: The URL to the script to load.

/web/svg/element/script/attributes/type.name: type
/web/svg/element/script/attributes/type.summary: This attribute defines type of the script language to use.

/web/svg/element/script/attributes/xlink.name: xlink:href
/web/svg/element/script/attributes/xlink.summary: The URL to the script to load.

/web/svg/element/set.name: set
/web/svg/element/set.summary: The SVG `<set>` element provides a simple means of just setting the value of an attribute for a specified duration.

/web/svg/element/set/attributes/to.name: to
/web/svg/element/set/attributes/to.summary: This attribute defines the value to be applied to the target attribute for the duration of the animation. The value must match the requirements of the target attribute.

/web/svg/element/stop.name: stop
/web/svg/element/stop.summary: The SVG `<stop>` element defines a color and its position to use on a gradient. This element is always a child of a linearGradient or radialGradient element.

/web/svg/element/stop/attributes/offset.name: offset
/web/svg/element/stop/attributes/offset.summary: This attribute defines where the gradient stop is placed along the gradient vector.

/web/svg/element/stop/attributes/stop-co.name: stop-color
/web/svg/element/stop/attributes/stop-co.summary: This attribute defines the color of the gradient stop. It can be used as a CSS property.

/web/svg/element/stop/attributes/stop-op.name: stop-opacity
/web/svg/element/stop/attributes/stop-op.summary: This attribute defines the opacity of the gradient stop. It can be used as a CSS property.

/web/svg/element/style.name: style
/web/svg/element/style.summary: The SVG `<style>` element allows style sheets to be embedded directly within SVG content.

/web/svg/element/style/attributes/type.name: type
/web/svg/element/style/attributes/type.summary: This attribute defines type of the style sheet language to use as a media type string.

/web/svg/element/style/attributes/media.name: media
/web/svg/element/style/attributes/media.summary: This attribute defines to which  the style applies.

/web/svg/element/style/attributes/title.name: title
/web/svg/element/style/attributes/title.summary: This attribute the title of the style sheet which can be used to switch between alternate style sheets.

/web/svg/element/svg.name: svg
/web/svg/element/svg.summary: The `svg` element is a container that defines a new coordinate system and viewport. It is used as the outermost element of SVG documents, but it can also be used to embed an SVG fragment inside an SVG or HTML document.

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/baseProf.name: baseProfile
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/baseProf.summary: The minimum SVG language profile that the document requires.

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/contentS.name: contentScriptType
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/contentS.summary: The default scripting language used by the SVG fragment.

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/contentS.name: contentStyleType
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/contentS.summary: The default style sheet language used by the SVG fragment.

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/height.name: height
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/height.summary: The displayed height of the rectangular viewport. (Not the height of its coordinate system.)

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/preserve.name: preserveAspectRatio
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/preserve.summary: How the `svg` fragment must be deformed if it is displayed with a different aspect ratio.

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/version.name: version
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/version.summary: Which version of SVG is used for the inner content of the element.

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/viewBox.name: viewBox
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/viewBox.summary: The SVG viewport coordinates for the current SVG fragment.

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/width.name: width
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/width.summary: The displayed width of the rectangular viewport. (Not the width of its coordinate system.)

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/x.name: x
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/x.summary: The displayed x coordinate of the svg container. No effect on outermost `svg` elements.

/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/y.name: y
/web/svg/element/svg/attributes/y.summary: The displayed y coordinate of the svg container. No effect on outermost `svg` elements.

/web/svg/element/switch.name: switch
/web/svg/element/switch.summary: The `<switch>` SVG element evaluates any requiredFeatures, requiredExtensions and systemLanguage attributes on its direct child elements in order, and then renders the first child where these attributes evaluate to true.

/web/svg/element/symbol.name: symbol
/web/svg/element/symbol.summary: The `<symbol>` element is used to define graphical template objects which can be instantiated by a use element.

/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/heigh.name: height
/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/heigh.summary: This attribute determines the height of the symbol.

/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/prese.name: preserveAspectRatio
/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/prese.summary: This attribute defines how the svg fragment must be deformed if it is embedded in a container with a different aspect ratio.

/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/refX.name: refX
/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/refX.summary: This attribute determines the x coordinate of the reference point of the symbol.

/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/refY.name: refY
/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/refY.summary: This attribute determines the y coordinate of the reference point of the symbol.

/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/viewB.name: viewBox
/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/viewB.summary: This attribute defines the bound of the SVG viewport for the current symbol.

/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/width.name: width
/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/width.summary: This attribute determines the width of the symbol.

/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/x.name: x
/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/x.summary: This attribute determines the x coordinate of the symbol.

/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/y.name: y
/web/svg/element/symbol/attributes/y.summary: This attribute determines the y coordinate of the symbol.

/web/svg/element/text.name: text
/web/svg/element/text.summary: The SVG `<text>` element draws a graphics element consisting of text. It's possible to apply a gradient, pattern, clipping path, mask, or filter to `<text>`, like any other SVG graphics element.

/web/svg/element/text/attributes/x.name: x
/web/svg/element/text/attributes/x.summary: The x coordinate of the starting point of the text baseline.

/web/svg/element/text/attributes/y.name: y
/web/svg/element/text/attributes/y.summary: The y coordinate of the starting point of the text baseline.

/web/svg/element/text/attributes/dx.name: dx
/web/svg/element/text/attributes/dx.summary: Shifts the text position horizontally from a previous text element.

/web/svg/element/text/attributes/dy.name: dy
/web/svg/element/text/attributes/dy.summary: Shifts the text position vertically from a previous text element.

/web/svg/element/text/attributes/rotate.name: rotate
/web/svg/element/text/attributes/rotate.summary: Rotates orientation of each individual glyph. Can rotate glyphs individually.

/web/svg/element/text/attributes/lengthA.name: lengthAdjust
/web/svg/element/text/attributes/lengthA.summary: How the text is stretched or compressed to fit the width defined by the `textLength` attribute.

/web/svg/element/text/attributes/textLen.name: textLength
/web/svg/element/text/attributes/textLen.summary: A width that the text should be scaled to fit.

/web/svg/element/textpath.name: textPath
/web/svg/element/textpath.summary: To render text along the shape of a path, enclose the text in a `<textPath>` element that has an href attribute with a reference to the path element.

/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/hre.name: href
/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/hre.summary: The URL to the path or basic shape on which to render the text. If the `path` attribute is set, `href` has no effect.

/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/len.name: lengthAdjust
/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/len.summary: Where length adjustment should be applied to the text: the space between glyphs, or both the space and the glyphs themselves.

/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/met.name: method
/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/met.summary: Which method to render individual glyphs along the path.

/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/pat.name: path
/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/pat.summary: The path on which the text should be rendered.

/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/sid.name: side
/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/sid.summary: Which side of the path the text should be rendered.

/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/spa.name: spacing
/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/spa.summary: How space between glyphs should be handled.

/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/sta.name: startOffset
/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/sta.summary: How far the beginning of the text should be offset from the beginning of the path.

/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/tex.name: textLength
/web/svg/element/textpath/attributes/tex.summary: The width of the space into which the text will render.

/web/svg/element/title.name: title
/web/svg/element/title.summary: The `<title>` element provides an accessible, short-text description of any SVG container element or graphics element.

/web/svg/element/tref.name: tref
/web/svg/element/tref.summary: The textual content for a text SVG element can be either character data directly embedded within the text element or the character data content of a referenced element, where the referencing is specified with a `<tref>` element.

/web/svg/element/tspan.name: tspan
/web/svg/element/tspan.summary: The SVG `<tspan>` element defines a subtext within a  element or another `<tspan>` element. It allows for adjustment of the style and/or position of that subtext as needed.

/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/x.name: x
/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/x.summary: The x coordinate of the starting point of the text baseline.

/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/y.name: y
/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/y.summary: The y coordinate of the starting point of the text baseline.

/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/dx.name: dx
/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/dx.summary: Shifts the text position horizontally from a previous text element.

/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/dy.name: dy
/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/dy.summary: Shifts the text position vertically from a previous text element.

/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/rotate.name: rotate
/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/rotate.summary: Rotates orientation of each individual glyph. Can rotate glyphs individually.

/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/length.name: lengthAdjust
/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/length.summary: How the text is stretched or compressed to fit the width defined by the `textLength` attribute.

/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/textLe.name: textLength
/web/svg/element/tspan/attributes/textLe.summary: A width that the text should be scaled to fit.

/web/svg/element/use.name: use
/web/svg/element/use.summary: The `<use>` element takes nodes from within the SVG document, and duplicates them somewhere else.

/web/svg/element/use/attributes/href.name: href
/web/svg/element/use/attributes/href.summary: The URL to an element/fragment that needs to be duplicated.

/web/svg/element/use/attributes/xlink:hr.name: xlink:href
/web/svg/element/use/attributes/xlink:hr.summary: An <IRI> reference to an element/fragment that needs to be duplicated.

/web/svg/element/use/attributes/x.name: x
/web/svg/element/use/attributes/x.summary: The x coordinate of the use element.

/web/svg/element/use/attributes/y.name: y
/web/svg/element/use/attributes/y.summary: The y coordinate of the use element.

/web/svg/element/use/attributes/width.name: width
/web/svg/element/use/attributes/width.summary: The width of the use element.

/web/svg/element/use/attributes/height.name: height
/web/svg/element/use/attributes/height.summary: The height of the use element.

/web/svg/element/view.name: view
/web/svg/element/view.summary: A view is a defined way to view the image, like a zoom level or a detail view.

/web/svg/element/vkern.name: vkern
/web/svg/element/vkern.summary: The `<vkern>` SVG element allows to fine-tweak the vertical distance between two glyphs in top-to-bottom fonts. This process is known as kerning.

/web/mathml/element/maction.name: maction
/web/mathml/element/maction.summary: The MathML `<maction>` element provides a possibility to bind actions to (sub-) expressions. The action itself is specified by the `actiontype` attribute, which accepts several values. To specify which child elements are addressed by the action, you can make use of the `selection` attribute.

/web/mathml/element/math.name: math
/web/mathml/element/math.summary: The top-level element in MathML is `<math>`. Every valid MathML instance must be wrapped in `<math>` tags. In addition you must not nest a second `<math>` element in another, but you can have an arbitrary number of other child elements in it.

/web/mathml/element/menclose.name: menclose
/web/mathml/element/menclose.summary: The MathML `<menclose>` element renders its content inside an enclosing notation specified by the `notation` attribute.

/web/mathml/element/merror.name: merror
/web/mathml/element/merror.summary: The MathML `<merror>` element is used to display contents as error messages. In Firefox this error message is rendered similar to the typical XML error message. Note that this error is not thrown when your MathML markup is wrong or not well-formed XML. You will still get an XML parsing error (in case of the XHTML notation of MathML), which has nothing to do with `<merror>`.

/web/mathml/element/mfenced.name: mfenced
/web/mathml/element/mfenced.summary: The deprecated MathML `<mfenced>` element used to provide the possibility to add custom opening and closing parentheses (such as brackets) and separators (such as commas or semicolons) to an expression. It has been removed from the latest MathML standard and modern browsers no longer support it. Use the mrow and mo elements instead.

/web/mathml/element/mfrac.name: mfrac
/web/mathml/element/mfrac.summary: The MathML `<mfrac>` element is used to display fractions.

/web/mathml/element/mi.name: mi
/web/mathml/element/mi.summary: The MathML `<mi>` element indicates that the content should be rendered as an identifier such as function names, variables or symbolic constants. You can also have arbitrary text in it to mark up terms.

/web/mathml/element/mmultiscripts.name: mmultiscripts
/web/mathml/element/mmultiscripts.summary: The MathML `<mmultiscripts>` element allows you to create tensor-like objects. In a descriptive way tensors are multidimensional matrices (mathematical imprecise but exemplified). The degree of a tensor depends on the dimensionality of a representative array. For example, a number is a 0-dimensional array, or a 0th-order tensor. A 1-dimensional array (e.g. vectors) is a 1st-order tensor and so 2nd-order tensors are needed to represent square matrices. To learn more about the mathematical background of tensors refer to the entry on Wikipedia.

/web/mathml/element/mn.name: mn
/web/mathml/element/mn.summary: The MathML `<mn>` element represents a numeric literal which is normally a sequence of digits with a possible separator (a dot or a comma). However,  it is also allowed to have arbitrary text in it which is actually a numeric quantity, for example "eleven".

/web/mathml/element/mo.name: mo
/web/mathml/element/mo.summary: The MathML `<mo>` element represents an operator in a broad sense. Besides operators in strict mathematical meaning, this element also includes "operators" like parentheses, separators like comma and semicolon, or "absolute value" bars.

/web/mathml/element/mover.name: mover
/web/mathml/element/mover.summary: The MathML `<mover>` element is used to attach an accent or a limit over an expression. Use the following syntax: `<mover> base overscript </mover>`

/web/mathml/element/mpadded.name: mpadded
/web/mathml/element/mpadded.summary: The MathML `<mpadded>` element is used to add extra padding and to set the general adjustment of position and size of enclosed contents.

/web/mathml/element/mphantom.name: mphantom
/web/mathml/element/mphantom.summary: The MathML `<mphantom>` element is rendered invisibly, but dimensions (such as height, width, and baseline position) are still kept.

/web/mathml/element/mroot.name: mroot
/web/mathml/element/mroot.summary: The MathML `<mroot>` element is used to display roots with an explicit index. Two arguments are accepted, which leads to the syntax: `<mroot> base index </mroot>`.

/web/mathml/element/mrow.name: mrow
/web/mathml/element/mrow.summary: The MathML `<mrow>` element is used to group sub-expressions, which usually contain one or more operators with their respective operands (such as mi and mn). This element renders as a horizontal row containing its arguments.

/web/mathml/element/ms.name: ms
/web/mathml/element/ms.summary: The MathML `<ms>` element represents a string literal meant to be interpreted by programming languages and computer algebra systems. By default, string literals are displayed as enclosed by double quotes (`"`); by using the `lquote` and `rquote` attributes, you can set custom characters to display. Note that quotation marks should not be specified unless they are part of the string literal. The content of an `<ms>` element is not an ASCII string per se, but rather a sequence of characters and malignmark elements.

/web/mathml/element/mspace.name: mspace
/web/mathml/element/mspace.summary: The MathML `<mspace>` element is used to display a blank space, whose size is set by its attributes.

/web/mathml/element/msqrt.name: msqrt
/web/mathml/element/msqrt.summary: The MathML `<msqrt>` element is used to display square roots (no index is displayed). The square root accepts only one argument, which leads to the following syntax: `<msqrt> base </msqrt>`.

/web/mathml/element/mstyle.name: mstyle
/web/mathml/element/mstyle.summary: The MathML `<mstyle>` element is used change the style of its children. It accepts all attributes of all MathML presentation elements with some exceptions and additional attributes listed below.

/web/mathml/element/msub.name: msub
/web/mathml/element/msub.summary: The MathML `<msub>` element is used to attach a subscript to an expression.

/web/mathml/element/msubsup.name: msubsup
/web/mathml/element/msubsup.summary: The MathML `<msubsup>` element is used to attach both a subscript and a superscript, together, to an expression.

/web/mathml/element/msup.name: msup
/web/mathml/element/msup.summary: The MathML `<msup>` element is used to attach a superscript to an expression.

/web/mathml/element/mtable.name: mtable
/web/mathml/element/mtable.summary: The MathML `<mtable>` element allows you to create tables or matrices. Inside a `<mtable>` only mtr and mtd elements may appear. These elements are similar to table , tr and td elements of HTML.

/web/mathml/element/mtd.name: mtd
/web/mathml/element/mtd.summary: The MathML `<mtd>` element represents a cell in a table or a matrix. It may only appear in a mtr element. This element is similar to the td element of HTML.

/web/mathml/element/mtext.name: mtext
/web/mathml/element/mtext.summary: The MathML <mtext> element is used to render arbitrary text with no notational meaning, such as comments or annotations.

/web/mathml/element/mtr.name: mtr
/web/mathml/element/mtr.summary: The MathML `<mtr>` element represents a row in a table or a matrix. It may only appear in a mtable element. This element is similar to the tr element of HTML.

/web/mathml/element/munder.name: munder
/web/mathml/element/munder.summary: The MathML `<munder>` element is used to attach an accent or a limit under an expression. It uses the following syntax: `<munder> base underscript </munder>`

/web/mathml/element/munderover.name: munderover
/web/mathml/element/munderover.summary: The MathML `<munderover>` element is used to attach accents or limits both under and over an expression.

/web/mathml/element/semantics.name: semantics
/web/mathml/element/semantics.summary: In MathML there are two ways to mark up mathematics: Presentation MathML is used to control the layout of equations, whereas Content MathML is designed to encode the semantic mathematical meaning and to make expressions understandable to computer algebra systems. The MathML elements `<semantics>`, `<annotation>` and `<annotation-xml>` are used to combine presentation and content markup and to provide both, layout information and semantic meaning of mathematical expressions.
